<HEAD>PROLOG</HEAD>
<HEAD>&THORN;is is &thorn;e prolog.  Capitulum .I<SUP>m</SUP>..</HEAD>
<P>God &thorn;at is good in him silf.  faire in hise aungelis. merveilouse|in hise seintis. and merciful vpon synners&meper; haue merci on vs now|&amp; euer/ and &yogh;yue vs grace to holde &thorn;e weye of tru&thorn;e&meper; in &thorn;ise daies|of greet tribulacioun &Verbar; For now manye &thorn;at semeden to haue be|stable in vertu&meper; fallen from her holi purpose. dredyng losse of|worldli goodis &amp; bodili peyne as Crist sei&thorn;. Mat. xxiv<SUP>o</SUP>. 'Quoniam|habundabit iniquitas&meper; refrigescet caritas multorum'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Matt. xxiv. 12./ &thorn;at is to|seie.  &thorn;e greet plente and habundaunce of wickidnesse&meper; schal kele|or make coolde. &thorn;e charite of many.<NOTE PLACE="foot">W. V. 'And for wickidness schal be plenteous, the charite of manye schal|wexe cold.'</NOTE>  For now &thorn;e deuel ha&thorn;|marrid &thorn;is world&meper; bi his leeftenaunt anticrist &thorn;at men ben born|aboute in diuerse dou&yogh;tis&meper; as wawis of &thorn;e see/ wrechidli diuidid</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="2a">| in wonderful opyniouns&meper; iche nei&yogh;bore wi&thorn; o&thorn;ir &Verbar; But | Seint Poul|sett oon acorde&meper; in al cristendom &amp; sei&thorn;.  Eph. iv<SUP>o</SUP>. 'Vnus|dominus vna fides vnum baptisma' &Verbar; &thorn;at is to seie. &thorn;er is but oo|lord&meper; &thorn;at alle men schulden drede &amp; loue/ oo fei&thorn;&meper; &thorn;at alle men|schulden bileue wi&thorn;outen chaungyng/ oo baptem or cristendom&meper;|&thorn;at alle men schulden kepe wi&thorn;outen defouling &Verbar; Alas hou is &thorn;is|oonhed or vnite broken.  &thorn;at men vnrulid walken aftir her lustis.|as beestis in &thorn;e corne? certis &thorn;e wickid man &thorn;at Crist speki&thorn; of&meper;|ha&thorn; done &thorn;is dede/ Mat. xiii<SUP>o</SUP>. 'Inimicus homo superseminauit|zizaunia'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Matt. xiii. 25 'Inimicus eius superseminavit zizania'; but v. 28|'Inimicus homo hoc fecit.'</NOTE> &Verbar; &THORN;at is to seie.  &thorn;e enemy of God ha&thorn; sowen taaris&meper;|vpon &thorn;e seed of Iesu Crist<NOTE PLACE="foot">W. V. 'His enemy cam and sew above dernel (or cokil) in the midil of|whete.'  1388, 'His enemy cam and sewe above taris,' etc.</NOTE> &Verbar; &THORN;is wickid man is anticrist&meper; &thorn;at|clowti&thorn; his lawis as roten raggis. to &thorn;e clene clo&thorn; of Cristis gospel/|&amp; waki&thorn; in malise as Iudas childe&meper; whilis Symon slepi&thorn; &amp; taki&thorn;|noon hede &Verbar; O &thorn;ou wickid man. is &thorn;er ony o&thorn;ir &thorn;at may saue
<PB N="3">|soulis &thorn;an Crist Iesu?  God sei&thorn; bi &thorn;e mou&thorn;e of Moyses.  Deuto.|xxxii<SUP>o</SUP>. 'percuciam &amp; ego sanabo &amp; non est qui de manu | mea <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="2b">|possit eruere'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Deut. xxxii. 39.</NOTE> &Verbar; &thorn;at is to seie.  I schal smyt &amp; I schal heele&meper; &|&thorn;er is non &thorn;at mai skape fro myn hand<NOTE PLACE="foot">W. V. 'I schal smyte &amp; I schal heel, &amp; there is not that fro myn hoond|may delyver.'  1388, 'I schale smyte, and I schal make hool; and noon is|that may delivere fro myn hond.'</NOTE> &Verbar; Who ha&thorn; &thorn;e keies of|Daui&thorn; to opyn heuene &yogh;atis&meper; &amp; &thorn;anne noon o&thorn;ir closi&thorn; to close&meper;|&amp; &thorn;anne noon o&thorn;ir opyne&thorn;? Seint Jon sei&thorn;, Apoc. iii<SUP>o</SUP>. 'Sanctus &|verus habet clauem dauid qui aperit &amp; nemo claudit. claudit &|nemo aperit'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Apoc. iii. 7 'Haec dicit Sanctus &amp; Verus qui habet,' etc.</NOTE> &Verbar; &THORN;at is to seie.  Holi &amp; trewe Crist Iesu ha&thorn; &thorn;e|keie of Daui&thorn; &thorn;e whiche opine&thorn; &amp; noon o&thorn;ir closi&thorn;/ closi&thorn;&meper; &|&thorn;anne noon o&thorn;ir opine&thorn;&meper;/ who dinge&thorn; doun and &thorn;anne no man|reri&thorn;/ who reri&thorn;&meper; &amp; &thorn;anne no man dinge&thorn; doun.  Iob sei&thorn;. xii<SUP>o</SUP>.|'Si destruxerit nemo est qui edificet&meper; si incluserit hominem nullus|est qui apariat'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Job xii. 14.</NOTE> &Verbar; &THORN;at is to seie. whanne &thorn;e Lord God ha&thorn; distroied&meper;|&thorn;er may noon o&thorn;ir bijlde/ &amp; whanne &thorn;e Lord God stressi&thorn; a man in &thorn;e|prisoun&meper; &thorn;er mai noon o&thorn;ir delyuer him. ne quite him from hise|boondis<NOTE PLACE="foot">W. V. 'If he destro&yogh;e, no man is that bilde up; if he inclose a man, no|man is that opene.'  1388, 'If he destrieth, no man is that bildith, if he|schitteth in a man, noon is that openeth.'</NOTE> &Verbar; And &thorn;erfore in &thorn;e vertu of &thorn;is name Iesu&meper; stondi&thorn; al mannes|saluacioun/ as it is writen. Actus iv<SUP>o</SUP>. 'Nec enim aliud nomen est|sub celo datum hominibus vnde oporteat nos saluos fieri'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Act. iv. 12 'Nec enim aliud nomen est ... in quo,' etc.</NOTE> &Verbar; Seint|Petir sei&thorn;. &thorn;er | is noon o&thorn;ir name vndir heuene &yogh;yuen to men&meper; <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="3a">|but &thorn;is name Iesu. in &thorn;e whiche it bihoue&thorn; vs to be made saaf/|for oonli in vertu of &thorn;is name&meper; come&thorn; remyssioun of synnes/ as it|is writen Luc. xxiiii<SUP>o</SUP>. 'Oportebat predicari in nomine eius penitenciam|&amp; remissionem peccatorum in omnes gentes'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Luc. xxiv. 47.</NOTE> &Verbar; &thorn;at is to|seie.  It bihoued to be prechid among alle folkis&meper; penaunce &|remissioun of synnes in &thorn;e name of Iesu &Verbar; Art not &thorn;ou &thorn;anne|a wickid man. a foultid schepard, a cruel beest. &thorn;e sone of perdicioun|&amp; anticrist him silf. &thorn;at pretendist in &thorn;ee &amp; in &thorn;i membris|to bynde &amp; lose. to blesse &amp; curse. biside &thorn;is name Iesu?  Peple|wi&thorn;outen noumbre. folowyng &thorn;ee &amp; &thorn;i diuided lawis&meper; ben diuidid|from Crist Iesu/ &amp; gon wi&thorn; &thorn;ee blyndlingis&meper; to helle for euere-more/
<PB N="4">|And &thorn;is is greetli to sorow. so ferfor&thorn;e&meper; &thorn;at Crist maki&thorn;|mornyng &thorn;ervpon &amp; sei&thorn;. Ion v<SUP>o</SUP>. 'Ego veni in nomine patris mei|&amp; non accepistis me&meper; si alius venerit in nomine eius illum<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="3b">| accipietis'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Joh. v. 43.</NOTE> &Verbar; &thorn;at is to seie. | I haue comen in &thorn;e name of my|fadir&meper; &amp; &yogh;e haue not taken me/ whanne ano&thorn;ir come&thorn; in his|owene name&meper; him &yogh;e schal take/<NOTE PLACE="foot">W. V. 'I cam in the name of my fadir, &amp; &yogh;e token not me.  If another|schal come in his owne name, &yogh;e schulen receyve him.'</NOTE>  And &thorn;is is anticrist as seint|Ion Crisostum sei&thorn; vpon &thorn;is gospel.<NOTE PLACE="foot">S. Ioan. Chrysostomus, <I>Homilia XXVII in cap. Matt. xi (Opera,</I> ed.|1547, tom. ii, col. 913).</NOTE>  Mat. xi<SUP>o</SUP>.  'Tu es qui|venturus es an alium expectamus'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Matt. xi. 3.</NOTE> &Verbar; For who &thorn;at wole not|resceyue Crist&meper; in peyne of synne he is compellid &amp; constreyned|to resceyue anticrist &Verbar;  &THORN;erfore in &thorn;is tyme of hidouse derknes|somme seeken &thorn;e lanterne of li&yogh;t. of &thorn;e whiche speki&thorn; &thorn;e prophete.|Ps. cxviii. 'Lucerna pedibus meis verbum tuum'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Ps. cxviii. 105.</NOTE> &Verbar; &thorn;at is to seie.|Lord &thorn;i word is a lanterne to my feet.<NOTE PLACE="foot">W. V. 'Lanterne to my feet thi woord.'  1388, 'Thi word is a lanterne|to my feet.'</NOTE>/  For as fer as &thorn;e li&yogh;t of &thorn;is|lanterne schine&thorn;&meper; so fer derkness of synne &amp; cloudis of &thorn;e fendis|temptaciouns vanischen awey &amp; moun not abide/ And algatis|whanne &thorn;e lanterne li&yogh;tne&thorn; into &thorn;e hert&meper; it purge&thorn; &amp; clensi&thorn; from|corrupcioun/ it swagi&thorn; &amp; heeli&thorn; goostli soris/ As &thorn;e wise man|sei&thorn;.  Sap. xvi<SUP>o</SUP>.  'Neque herba neque malagma sanauit illos&meper;<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="4a">| sed | omnipotens sermo tuus domine qui sanat vniuersa'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Sap. xvi. 12 'Neque herba neque malagma sanavit eos, sed tuus,|Domine, sermo qui sanat omnia.'</NOTE> &Verbar; &thorn;at is|to seie.  Nei&thorn;ir herbe ne plaistir ha&thorn; helid hem&meper; but Lord &thorn;i|mi&yogh;ti word &thorn;at heeli&thorn; alle &thorn;ingis/<NOTE PLACE="foot">W. V. 'Forsothe neither erbe, ne plastre helde them; but thi word, Lord|that heleth all thingus.'</NOTE> For Lord whanne &thorn;ou diedist|vpon &thorn;e cros&meper; &thorn;ou puttidist in &thorn;i word &thorn;e spirit of lijf/ &amp; &yogh;auest|to it power of quickenyng&meper; bi &thorn;in owene preciouse blood. as &thorn;ou|&thorn;i silf seist.  Ion. vi<SUP>o</SUP>. 'verba que ego locutus sum vobis spiritus|&amp; vita sunt'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Joh. vi. 64.</NOTE> &Verbar;  &thorn;at is to seie. &thorn;e wordis &thorn;at I speke to &yogh;ow&meper; &thorn;ei|ben spirit &amp; lijf &Verbar;</P></DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="2">
<PB N="5">
<HEAD>Of a peticioun.  &Verbar; Capitulum .II<SUP>m</SUP>.. &Verbar;</HEAD>
<P>Dere frendis helpe me wi&thorn; &yogh;oure preiere&meper; anentis almi&yogh;ti God/|For seint Iame sei&thorn;/ v<SUP>o</SUP>. 'Multum valet deprecacio iusti assidua.'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Jac. v. 16.</NOTE> &Verbar;|&THORN;at is to seie. &thorn;e bisi preier of &thorn;e ri&yogh;twise&meper; is miche wor&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">W. V. 'The contynuel preyer of a just man is miche worth.'</NOTE> &Verbar; &thorn;is|&yogh;oure axing &amp; &yogh;oure desire&meper; is ful chargouse to me/ but anentis|God&meper; no &thorn;ing is vnpossible.  as Crist sei&thorn;/ Mat. xix<SUP>o</SUP>. Mar. x<SUP>o</SUP>.|Luc. xviii<SUP>o</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Matt. xix. 26, Marc. x. 27, Luc. xviii. 27; W. V. 'Anentis God|alle &thorn;ingis ben possible.'</NOTE>/ And in &thorn;is fei&thorn; Isaie seid. xxvi<SUP>o</SUP>. 'Deus ipse operatur|omnia opera nostra in nobis'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Isaias xxvi. 12 'Domine, dabis pacem nobis: omnia enim opera|nostra operatus es nobis.'</NOTE> &Verbar; &thorn;at is to seie. &thorn;e Lord God|him silf worchi&thorn; | alle oure werkis in vs<NOTE PLACE="foot">W. V. 'Alle forsothe oure werkis thou wro&yogh;tist in us.'</NOTE> &Verbar; Faile we not God <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="4b">|&thorn;anne in good lyuyng&meper; &amp; he mai not faile to &yogh;yue vs suche wisdam|as is nedful to vs/ &amp; also to stere yne oure toung. &amp; &yogh;yue vs trewe|organ of redi eloquens to edifiyng of oure nei&yogh;bour as Crist sei&thorn;|Mat. x<SUP>o</SUP>. 'Non enim vos estis qui loquimini&meper; sed spiritus patris|vestri qui loquitur in vobis'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Matt. x. 20.</NOTE> &Verbar; &thorn;at is to seie.  Forso&thorn;e it arne not|&yogh;e &thorn;at speken but &thorn;e spirit of &yogh;oure fadir &thorn;at speki&thorn; in &yogh;ou/ For|&thorn;e apostlis of Crist &amp; o&thorn;ir seintis&meper; weren not graduat men in scolis/|but &thorn;e Holi Goost sodenli enspirid hem&meper; &amp; maden hem plenteuous|of heuenli loore. &amp; &thorn;ei &thorn;at han traueilid in deedli lettirs&meper; mekid|hem silf as symple ydiotis as seint Ierom sei&thorn;/ 'Predicatores|illiterati mittuntur ad predicandum vt fides credencium.  non|virtute humana sed eloquencia &amp; virtute dei fieri putaretur'/|Hec Ieromus super Mat. li<SUP>o</SUP>. Io/<NOTE PLACE="foot">S. Hieronymus, <I>Comment. in Evan. Matt.,</I> Lib. I, cap. iv, v. 19, 20|(Migne, tom. 26, col. 33).</NOTE> &THORN;at is to seie. prechours|vnlettrid&meper; ben sent for to preche &thorn;at &thorn;e fei&thorn; of trewe|bileuars&meper; schulde be hopid to be brou&yogh;t in/ not bi mannes | vertu&meper; <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="5a">|but bi speche &amp; doctrine of God/  And so sei&thorn; seint Austin|writing to Symplician &Verbar; 'Quid patimur? quid audimus? surgunt|indocti &amp; celum rapiunt&meper; &amp; nos cum doctrinis nostris in infernum|dimergimur &Verbar;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Augustinus, <I>Confessiones,</I> Lib. VIII, cap. viii (Migne, tom. 32. col. 757).</NOTE> &THORN;at is to seie. what suffren we? what heeren we?/|vntau&yogh;t men risen &amp; cacchen heuene. &amp; we wi&thorn; oure clergie ben
<PB N="6">|drowned to helle &Verbar;  And seint Gregor in hise morals&meper; afferme&thorn; &thorn;is|sentence &amp; sei&thorn;/  Sicut incarnata veritas in predicacione sua|pauperes symplices &amp; ydiotas elegit&meper; sicut e contra antichristus ad|predicandum falsitatem suam astutos &amp; dupplices &amp; huius mundi|sapienciam habentes electurus est<NOTE PLACE="foot">Gregorius Magnus, <I>Moralium</I> Lib. XIII, cap. x. 13 (Migne, tom. 75,|col. 1023).</NOTE> &Verbar; &thorn;at is to seie. ri&yogh;t as trou&thorn;e|incarnat. &thorn;at is Crist in manhood chase pore symple &amp; ydiotis to|his prechyng/ so a&yogh;enwarde anticrist is for to chese&meper; sturdi &|duble men/ &amp; hauyng &thorn;e wisedom of &thorn;is world&meper; for to preche his|falshede/ Haue we &thorn;anne ful fei&thorn;&meper; in &thorn;is Lord Iesu wi&thorn; perfite<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="5b">| lyuyng/ &amp; &thorn;is Lord &thorn;oru&yogh; | &yogh;oure preiour&meper; schal lede &thorn;is werke|aftir his owene plesaunce/ &amp; bring it to a perfite ende to his owene|worschip&meper; &amp; profite of hise seruauntis &Verbar;</P>
