<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="3">
<HEAD>What is anticrist in general wi&thorn; .VI. condiciouns/</HEAD>
<HEAD>Capitulum .III<SUP>m</SUP>..</HEAD>
<P>To speke in general&meper; &thorn;at is in moost in comune/ anticrist is|euery man&meper; &thorn;at lyue&thorn; a&yogh;en Crist/ as seint Ion sei&thorn;.  Ion. ii<SUP>o</SUP>.|'Nunc autem sunt multi antichristi'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. 1 Joh. ii. 18 'Nunc antichristi multi facti sunt.'</NOTE>/  &thorn;at is to seie. forso&thorn;e|now ben manye anticristis<NOTE PLACE="foot">W V. 'Now many antecristes ben made.'</NOTE>/ And &thorn;erfore sei&thorn; seint Austin. who|&thorn;at lyue&thorn; contrarie to Crist&meper; he is an anticrist/ be &thorn;ou wi&thorn;ynne|be &thorn;ou wi&thorn;oute&meper; &amp; &thorn;ou lyue contrarie to Crist. &thorn;ou arte but|chaff<NOTE PLACE="foot">Augustinus, <I>Ep. Ioan</I>., Tract. III. 89 (Migne, tom. 35, col. 2001,|2002).</NOTE>/ of &thorn;e whiche chaff Crist. Mat. iii<SUP>o</SUP>. 'Paleas autem conburet|igni inextinguibli'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Matt. iii. 12.</NOTE>/ &thorn;at is to seie.  Forso&thorn;e &thorn;e chaff schal|brenne&meper; wi&thorn; fire &thorn;at mai not be quenchid<NOTE PLACE="foot">W. V. 'But chaffis he schal brenne with fyr unquenchable.'  1388, 'But|the chaffe he schal brenne with fier that mai not be quenchid.'</NOTE>/ for it schal brenne|&amp; neuer quenche/ &amp; &thorn;e soule &thorn;at is chaff&meper; schal euere suffre &|neuer die. as &thorn;e prophete sei&thorn;. Isaie. ix<SUP>o</SUP>. 'Omnis violenta predacio<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="6a">| cum tumultu &amp; omne vestimentum commix-|-tum sanguine erit|in combustionem &amp; cibus ignis'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Isaias ix. 5 'Quia omnis violenta praedatio cum tumultu et vestimentum|mistum sanguine,' etc.</NOTE> &Verbar;  &THORN;at is to seie. euery proud|soule. &thorn;at risi&thorn; in swelling a&yogh;ens his God/ &amp; euery bodi &thorn;at is|defoulid&meper; in glotenye &amp; in leccherie/ schal be in to sweyling&meper; &amp;
<PB N="7">|mete of &thorn;e fire<NOTE PLACE="foot">W. V. 'For eche violent reuyng with noise, &amp; clothing mengd with blod|shal be in to brennyng, &amp; mete of fyr.'</NOTE>/  As if he schulde seie. &thorn;e bodi &amp; &thorn;e soule|dampned&meper; schullen feed and norische &thorn;e fire/ &thorn;e whiche schal|euere brenne hem wi&thorn; moost greuous peyne.</P>
<P>Sixe synnes &thorn;er ben&meper; a&yogh;en &thorn;e Holi Goost/ &thorn;at turnen &thorn;e|wrecchid soule&meper; in to &thorn;is chaff/ But &thorn;e philosophur sei&thorn;. 'Nullum|malum vitatur nisi cognitum'/ &thorn;at is to seie. &thorn;er is non yuel fled&meper;|but if it be knowen/ &amp; &thorn;erfore we schullen name hem&meper; in &thorn;is|litil tretise/ for &thorn;e more lernyng&meper; of smale vndirstondars&Verbar;</P>
<P>&THORN;e firste of &thorn;ise synnes is presumpcioun.  &thorn;at is hi&yogh;e bolnyng|of &thorn;e spirit&meper; wi&thorn;outen drede of Goddis ri&yogh;twisenesse/ and of &thorn;is|synne al manere malice &amp; wickidnes cacchi&thorn; roote&meper; &thorn;at regne&thorn;|among mankynde in lewid | or in lerned. for &thorn;e wise man sei&thorn; <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="6b">|Ecc. i. 'Qui non timet non poterit iustificari'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Ecclesiasticus i. 28 'Nam qui sine timore est, non poterit iustificari.'</NOTE> &Verbar;  He &thorn;at dredi&thorn;|not&meper; he mai not be made ri&yogh;twise<NOTE PLACE="foot">W. V. 'For who withoute drede is, shal not moun be iustified.'  1388, 'He|that is without drede, mai not be iustified.'</NOTE>/ Forso&thorn;e in whom so &thorn;at &thorn;is|synne of presumpcioun ha&thorn; noo lordschipe&meper; in him &thorn;e deuel is|ouercomen. for it is writen. Ecc. xv<SUP>o</SUP>. 'Qui timet deum faciet|bona'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Ecclesiasticus xv. 1.</NOTE> &Verbar; He &thorn;at dredi&thorn; &thorn;e Lord&meper; schal do good &thorn;ingis/ &amp; &thorn;erfore|sei&thorn; &thorn;e Holi Goost<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. holgoost.</NOTE> Ecc. xxvii<SUP>o</SUP>. 'Si non in timore domini tenueris|te instanter. cito subuertetur domus tua'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Ecclesiasticus xxvii. 4.</NOTE>/ &Verbar;  &THORN;at is to seie. but if|&thorn;ou holde &thorn;e bisili in &thorn;e drede of &thorn;e Lord&meper; &thorn;in hous schal soone|be turned vpsodoun/ &thorn;at is. &thorn;i bodi &amp; &thorn;i soule schullen be turned|from God: into &thorn;e fendis seruice &Verbar;</P>
<P>&THORN;e secounde synne is desperacioun o&thorn;ir wanhope. &thorn;at is ouere litil|triste on &thorn;e merci of God &Verbar; Seint Austin sei&thorn;. 'Amare &amp; timere|sunt due ianue vite' &Verbar;  Drede of Goddis ri&yogh;twisenesse. &amp; hope of|Goddis merci&meper; ben twoo &yogh;atis of lijf/ for bi hem we entren here in|to grace&meper; and aftir in to blisse.  as &thorn;e prophet sei&thorn;. Ps. cxlvi.|'Bene placitum est Domino super timentes eum&meper; &amp; in eis qui &Verbar;sperant super misericordia eius'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Ps. cxlvi. 11.</NOTE> &Verbar;  It is wel plesid vnto &thorn;e Lord <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="7a">|vpon hem &thorn;at dreden him: &amp; in hem &thorn;at tristen on his mercy<NOTE PLACE="foot">W. V. 'Wel plesid thing is to the Lord upon men dredende hym; and in|hem that hopen on his mercy.'  1388, 'It is wel plesaunt to the Lord on men|that dreden him; and in hem that hopen on his mercy.'</NOTE> &Verbar;|And a&yogh;enwarde. presumpcioun &amp; disperacioun&meper; ben twoo &yogh;atis of
<PB N="8">|dee&thorn;/ bi &thorn;e whiche men entrien&meper; in to synne &amp; cumbraunce/ &|aftir in to &thorn;e peyne of helle&meper; wi&thorn;outen ende/ Seint Ion techi&thorn; vs|loore a&yogh;en &thorn;is synne&meper; &amp; sei&thorn;. Ion ii<SUP>o</SUP>. 'Filioli mei hec scribo vobis|vt non peccetis. sed &amp; si quis peccauerit aduocatum habemus apud|patrem Iesum Christum iustum &amp; ipse est propiciacio pro peccatis|nostris. non pro nostris tantum sed pro tocius mundi'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. 1 Joh. ii. 1.</NOTE> &Verbar;  Mi litil|sones. &thorn;ise &thorn;ingis I write vnto &yogh;ou&meper; &thorn;at &yogh;e synne not in &thorn;e synne|of dispeire/ but if it be so&meper; &thorn;at ony of vs haue synned/ we haue|avoket anenst &thorn;e fadir&meper; Iesu Crist oure iust lord. &amp; he is &thorn;e|mercy-asker for oure synnes/ not oonli for oure synnes&meper; but also|for &thorn;e synnes of al &thorn;e world<NOTE PLACE="foot">W. V. 'My litil sones, I wryte to &yogh;ou these thinges, that &yogh;e synne not.|But and if ony man shal synne, we han avoket anentis the fadir, Jhesu Crist|iust, &amp; he is helpyng for oure synnes; sotheli not onely for oure but also for|of al the world.'  1388, 'My litil sones ... we han an advocat anentis the|fadir, Jhesu Crist, and he is the for&yogh;yuenes for oure synnes.'</NOTE> &Verbar; Iesu is for to seie. a sauiour in|oure tung&meper; for he ha&thorn; plente of medicyn. to saue all mankynde|if &thorn;ei wolde take &thorn;is medicyn&meper; &amp; be saaf/ for Gregor sei&thorn;/ Se<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="7b">| ipsum in-|-terimit qui precepta medici obseruare non vult.  He|slee&thorn; him silf: &thorn;at wole not kepe &thorn;e biddingis of his leche &Verbar;</P>
<P>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde synne is obstinacioun or hardnes of herte/ &thorn;e whiche|wole not be contrit. for conpunccioun&meper; nei&thorn;ir be made softe wi&thorn;|pite/ ne mevid wi&thorn; preiours ne &thorn;retingis/ &amp; setti&thorn; nou&yogh;t bi betingis/|It is vnkynde a&yogh;en good dedis/ vnfei&thorn;ful to counseils/ feeris &|wood in doomes/ vnschamefast in foule &thorn;ingis/ nei&thorn;ir feerful in|perelis/ nei&thorn;ir manful in manhod/ foolhardi a&yogh;ens God/ for&yogh;etil of|tyme &thorn;at is passid/ necligent in tyme &thorn;at is present/ not purueiyng|for tyme &thorn;at is to cum/  And schortli for to seie. &thorn;is is &thorn;at synne&meper;|&thorn;at nei&thorn;ir dredi&thorn; God ne schame&thorn; man &Verbar; &THORN;us sei&thorn; seint Bernard .V.|distinccioun iiii<SUP>o</SUP>/  A medicyn for &thorn;is hard herte&meper; techi&thorn; Lincoln|where he sei&thorn;. diccio CVI. 'Cor durum debet conteri in mortarialo|petrino graui pila. mortarialum sunt vulnera christi. pila ex timore|pene peccati' &Verbar;  An harde herte wolde be braied in a morter wi&thorn;<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="8a">| an hevi pes-|-tel/ &thorn;is morter is &thorn;e bodi of Crist: hoolid or|woundid in his passioun/ &thorn;is pestel is &thorn;e drede of dampnacioun/|&thorn;at folowi&thorn; aftir &thorn;is synne &Verbar;  &THORN;anne &thorn;us &thorn;ou obstinat man. &thorn;ou|endurid man in synne.  &thorn;ou hard hertid wrecche&meper; nei&yogh;e &thorn;ou to &thorn;e|bodi of Crist/ &amp; for drede of dampnacioun&meper; conforme &thorn;ee to Cristis|passioun &Verbar;</P>
<P>
<PB N="9">&THORN;e four&thorn;e synne is fynali inrepentaunt&meper;  &thorn;at is he &thorn;at wole|neuer do verri penaunce/ but contynueli ledi&thorn; his lijf&meper; aftir &thorn;e|desiris of his fleische/ ouercomen wi&thorn; &thorn;e fende&meper; &amp; &thorn;e fals world &Verbar;|For no man do&thorn; verry penaunce to God.  but he &thorn;at fulli leue&thorn;|&thorn;at synne&meper; for &thorn;e whiche he suffri&thorn; penaunce/ &thorn;us sei&thorn; seint|Austin/  But for &thorn;ei holden it miche worschipe&meper; to write her|names in &thorn;e er&thorn;e/ &thorn;ei maken a feyned schrifte to a prest: &amp; taken|part of sacramentis/ &thorn;ei bilden chirches wi&thorn; o&thorn;er ournmentis&meper; &|fynden prestis to rede &amp; syng/ &thorn;ei releuen &thorn;e pore nedi&meper; &amp; menden|placis &thorn;at ben perilous/ but stille &thorn;ei lien harde | congelid as <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="8b">|froost&meper; in oolde custum of synne &Verbar;  To &thorn;ise vnrepentaunt men&meper;|speki&thorn; Gregor moost scharpli in hise pastorals. vpon &thorn;is tixte.|Mat. vi<SUP>o</SUP>.  'Nonne anima plus est quam esca&meper; &amp; corpus plus|quam vestimentum'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Matt. vi. 25.</NOTE> &Verbar; whe&thorn;ir is not &thorn;e lijf more &thorn;an mete&meper; &amp; &thorn;e|bodi more &thorn;an clo&thorn;e?  Vpon &thorn;is sei&thorn; &thorn;is doctour 'Qui cibum vel|vestem pauperibus largitur &amp; anime vel corporis iniquitate polluitur|quod magis est contulit culpe quod minus est contulit iusticie/ sua|dedit deo&meper; se ipsum diabolo'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Gregorius Magnus, <I>Regulae Pastoralis Liber</I> xliv (Migne, tom. 77,|col. 85).</NOTE>/  He &thorn;at &yogh;yue&thorn; mete or clo&thorn;e&meper; to|&thorn;e pore nedi/ &amp; is pollutid or defoulid&meper; in wickidenesse of bodi|&amp; of soule/ &thorn;at &thorn;ing &thorn;at is moost he &yogh;yue&thorn; to synne/ &thorn;at &thorn;ing &thorn;at|is leest he &yogh;yue&thorn; to ri&yogh;twisenesse/ hise goodis he &yogh;yue&thorn; to God&meper;|him silf to &thorn;e deuel/ for he setti&thorn; more prijs bi worldli richesse&meper;|&thorn;an he do&thorn; bi &thorn;e bodi or &thorn;e soule/ &amp; loue&thorn; moost &thorn;at God loue&thorn;|leest&meper; wherfore his loue is turned to hate &Verbar;  God ha&thorn; &yogh;ouun to|man&meper; fyue preciouse | &yogh;iftis.  &thorn;e leest of alle is worldli goodis/ <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="9a">|betir &thorn;an &thorn;ise is mannes bodi&meper; &thorn;at God ha&thorn; dowid wi&thorn; kyndeli|streng&thorn;is/ &amp; grauntid in resoun to vse &thorn;is world&meper; him silf to|chastise. cloo&thorn;e &amp; feede/  Abouen &thorn;ise tweyne is mannes soule&meper;|&thorn;at beri&thorn; Goddis ymage &amp; his licknes &Verbar;  Lord what profite were it|to wynne &thorn;is world&meper; &amp; putt peirement to &thorn;is soule? &amp; &thorn;e bodi is|a wlatful careyn&meper; whanne &thorn;e soule is goo &thorn;erfro/  But Goddis|grace passi&thorn; &thorn;ise &thorn;re. for where &thorn;is faili&thorn;. no wisdam availi&thorn; &Verbar;|Loke &thorn;ise ben not mys dispendid&meper; nei&thorn;ir worche oony &thorn;ing biside|&thorn;er ordir/ but &thorn;at &thorn;ei strecche alle to oo ende&meper; to wynne &thorn;e fif&thorn;e&meper;|&thorn;at is &thorn;e blisse of heuene for euere &Verbar;  &THORN;ou &thorn;at chaungist &thorn;is ordir
<PB N="10">|vpsodoun&meper; seint Poul axi&thorn; &thorn;is questioun of &thorn;e.  Ro. ii<SUP>o</SUP>. 'An|diuicias bonitatis eius &amp; paciencie &amp; longanimitatis contempnis?|Ignoras quoniam benignitas dei ad penitenciam te adducit/ secundum<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="9b">| autem duriciam tuam &amp; cor impenitens thesaurizas tibi | iram|in die ire &amp; reuelacionis iusti iudicii dei qui reddet vnicuique|secundum opera eius'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Rom. ii. 4, 5.</NOTE> &Verbar;  Whe&thorn;ir dispisist &thorn;ou &thorn;e richessis of &thorn;e|goodnes &amp; pacience &amp; longabiding of &thorn;i God? knowist &thorn;ou not|&thorn;at &thorn;e goodnes of God&meper; ledi&thorn; o&thorn;ir dryue&thorn; &thorn;ee to penaunce? forso&thorn;e|aftir &thorn;in hardnes &amp; &thorn;in vnrepentaunt herte.  &thorn;ou tresourist|to &thorn;ee wra&thorn;&thorn;e&meper; in &thorn;e dai of wra&thorn;&thorn;e/ &amp; schewing of ri&yogh;twise iugement|of God. &thorn;at schal &yogh;elde iche man&meper; aftir hise werkis<NOTE PLACE="foot">W. V. 'Wher thou dispisest the richessis of his goodnesse &amp; pacience &|longe abidyng?  Unknowest thou, for the benygnyte (or good wille) of God|ledith thee to penaunce?  Forsothe aftir thi hardnesse &amp; unrepentaunt herte,|thou tresourist to thee wra&thorn;&thorn;e in to the day of wraththe &amp; of schewynge of the|ri&yogh;tful dom of God, that schal &yogh;elde to ech man up his workis.'  1388,|'Whether dispisist thou the richessis of his goodnesse, and the pacience, and|the long abidyng?  Knowist thou not, that the benygnyte of God ledith thee|to forthenkyng?  But aftir thin hardnesse and unrepentaunt herte, thou|tresorist to thee wraththe in the dai of wraththe and of schewyng of the ri&yogh;tful|doom of God, that schal &yogh;elde to ech man aftir his werkis.'</NOTE> &Verbar;</P>
<P>&THORN;e fif&thorn;e synne is envie&meper; of &thorn;i bro&thorn;eris grace/ as whanne &thorn;i|nei&yogh;bour is wise. wel gouerned. preisid or born vp. riche. wel&thorn;i.|strong. faire. or vertuouse in greet habundaunce of grace.  &thorn;anne|&thorn;is enviouse man.  sclaundri&thorn;.  vpbreidi&thorn;.  reproue&thorn;.  dispisi&thorn;.|hati&thorn;. &amp; hyndri&thorn;. scorne&thorn;. &amp; pursue&thorn;.  to defoule &amp; waast his|bro&thorn;eris goodis &thorn;at ben goostli gracis&meper; as miche as he mai&meper;|as &thorn;e wise man sei&thorn; &Verbar; Prou. xiiii<SUP>o</SUP>. 'Ambulans recto itinere|&amp; timens deum. despicitur ab eo qui infami graditur via'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Prov. xiv. 2.</NOTE> &Verbar;<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="10a">| A man walking in | &thorn;e hi&yogh;e weie &amp; dreding God&meper; is dispisid of|him &thorn;at walki&thorn; in &thorn;e wrong weye/<NOTE PLACE="foot">W. V. 'The goende in ri&yogh;t weie, &amp; dredende God is dispised of hym that|goth in the evel losid weie.'  1388, 'A man goynge in ri&yogh;tful weie and dredinge|God, is dispisid of hym that goith in a weie of yuel fame.'</NOTE>  whanne Iesu Crist kest|out a deuel&meper; from a man &thorn;at was doumb. as it is writen.  Mat.|xii<SUP>o</SUP>. Marc. iii<SUP>o</SUP>. Luc. xi<SUP>o</SUP>.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Matt. xii. 22; Marc. iii. 11, 12; Luc. xi. 14.</NOTE> anoon &thorn;is man bigan to speke: to|puplische &thorn;is miracle among &thorn;e peple/ &THORN;anne scribis &amp; pharises|enviouse sectis&meper; &thorn;at weren a fals priuat religioun/ sclaundrid &thorn;at|Crist wrou&yogh;t &thorn;is miracle&meper; in Belsabub &thorn;at was prince of deuelis &Verbar;
<PB N="11">|Belsabub is to seie a god of fli&yogh;es&meper; or ellis a god &thorn;at maki&thorn; discorde/|Lord si&thorn;en &thorn;ise sectis dursten seie&meper; &thorn;us to Crist heed of|mannis soule/ hou miche werre schullen &thorn;ey moun dore seie&meper; to|hise hous-meyne?  &THORN;us prelatis &amp; freris in &thorn;ise daies&meper; ben traueilid|wi&thorn; &thorn;is synne a&yogh;en &thorn;e Holi Goost/ &amp; schamfulli sclaundren her|symple bri&thorn;eren&meper; &thorn;at casten yuel maners from her soule/ or|prechen &thorn;e gospel to Cristis entent&meper; to turne &thorn;e peple to vertuouse|lyuyng &Verbar;  &THORN;ei seien &thorn;is man ha&thorn; eten | a fli&yogh;e&meper; &thorn;at &yogh;yue&thorn; him lore <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="10b">|of Goddis lawe/ &thorn;is is more foule to eete a flie&meper; &thorn;an to be a god|&amp; chare &thorn;ise fli&yogh;es/ &THORN;us han &thorn;ey brou&yogh;t her malice aboute&meper; to|sclaundir for Lollardis &thorn;at speken of God/ &amp; dryuen &thorn;e peple|from &thorn;e fei&thorn;&meper; &thorn;at durne not worche ne speke for sclaundir/ but|certis &thorn;ey ben not wor&thorn;i Crist&meper; &thorn;at stony&eacute;n for barkyng of &thorn;ise|houndis/ for noon is wor&thorn;i to be wi&thorn; &thorn;is Lord&meper; &thorn;at schame&thorn; his|seruyse in wel or in woo/ &amp; suche men schewen hem traitours to|God&meper; &thorn;at wi&thorn; her sclaundris hindren her bri&thorn;eren/ &amp; seyn &thorn;e|fende mai &amp; wil&meper; make wise hise membris &thorn;at seruen him in|synne/ but so wole not Crist hise loued seruauntis&meper; &thorn;at lyuen in|clennes to serue him in vertu &Verbar; O I preie &yogh;ou&meper; who hard euer|a fouler blasfemye? certis &thorn;is dispit strecchi&thorn; vnto &thorn;e godhed&meper; to|be punyschid in &thorn;e dai of iugement/ for Goddis lawe techi&thorn;.|Prou. iii<SUP>o</SUP>.  'Noli prohibere benefacere qui potest si vales &amp; ipse|benefac'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Prov. iii. 27 'Noli prohibere benefacere eum qui potest,' etc.</NOTE> &Verbar;  Forbede him | not &thorn;at mai wel do&meper; but if &thorn;ou mai do <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="11a">|wel &thorn;i silf<NOTE PLACE="foot">W. V. 'Wile thou not forfenden hym that mai wel don, if thou maist, and|thiself wel do.'  1388, 'Nil thou forbede to do wel him that mai: if thou|maist, and do thou wel.'</NOTE> &Verbar; &THORN;at a prest schulde not be lettid&meper; to preche &thorn;e|trou&thorn;e/ ne Goddis peple to speke of her bileue&meper; is opunli tau&yogh;t|in &thorn;e book of Numeri xi<SUP>o</SUP>.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Num. xi. 24-30.</NOTE> &Verbar; &THORN;ere it is rad&meper; &thorn;at Heldad &amp; Medad|prophecied albeit &thorn;at &thorn;ei weren not lisensid bi Moises &Verbar; Iosue &thorn;e|mynyster of Moises. and chosen of manye&meper; grucchiden a&yogh;ens &thorn;ise|men. &amp; mad his pleynt to Moises/ &amp; Moises seide. whi art &thorn;ou|enviouse for me? who mai werne &thorn;at alle &thorn;e peple prophecie. &|God graunt his spirit to hem? &thorn;is is confermed in &thorn;e gospel of|oure Lord Iesu Crist&meper; bo&thorn;e in Mark ix<SUP>o</SUP> &amp; in Luc. ix<SUP>o</SUP>.  'Magister|vidimus quemdam in nomine tuo demonia eicientem qui non|sequitur nos &amp; prohibuimus eum/ Iesu autem ait/ Nolite prohibere
<PB N="12">|eum<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Marc. ix. 37, 38.</NOTE>'&Verbar; Seint Ion euaungelist seide vnto Crist. Maister|we han sen a man casting out deuelis in &thorn;i name. &thorn;at swe&thorn; not|vs&meper; &amp; we han forboden him/ forso&thorn;e Iesu seide.  Nile &yogh;e werne|him or forbeede him<NOTE PLACE="foot">W. V. 'Maister, we sy&yogh;en sum oon for to caste out fendis in thi name,|the which sueth not us, and we han forbedun him.  Sothli Jhesus seith to|him, Nile &yogh;e forbede him.'</NOTE> &Verbar; Alas howe dorne oure bischopis for<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="11b">| schame&meper; offende | a&yogh;ens &thorn;ise bo&thorn;e Goddis lawes/ &amp; docke her|prestis on euery side. to &yogh;yue hem a charge&meper; &amp; priue hem &thorn;er|office &Verbar;  What is to be sett biforne &thorn;e bodi of Crist &thorn;at prestis|sacren? And si&thorn;en &thorn;ei treten Cristis bodi. miche ra&thorn;er sei&thorn; Ierom|&thorn;ei schullen preche &amp; blesse &THORN;e peple. Hec dist. 99<NOTE PLACE="foot">Gratian, <I>Decreti</I> Pars Prima, dist. xcv, cap. v (Migne, tom. 187,|col. 449).</NOTE>.  But here|&thorn;e enemyes of tru&thorn;e obiectun &amp; leyn for hem Poul&meper; where he sei&thorn;|Ro. x<SUP>o</SUP>.  'Quomodo predicabunt nisi mittantur'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Rom. x. 15 'Quomodo vero praedicabunt,' etc.</NOTE> &Verbar;  How schullen|&thorn;ei preche but if &thorn;ei be sent?  wi&thorn; &thorn;is &thorn;ei blynden mani folk&meper;|kutting &thorn;e sentence from &thorn;e wordis/ for Poul mene&thorn; &thorn;at prestis|schulde preche&meper; for &thorn;ei ben sent/ bo&thorn;e of God &amp; of &thorn;e bischop&meper;|for to do &thorn;at office &Verbar;  And &thorn;e maister of sentence in his four&thorn;e|book &amp; &thorn;e XXIIII. dist. sei&thorn;/ It is &thorn;e office of a deken&meper; to preche|&thorn;e gospel<NOTE PLACE="foot">Petrus Lombardus, <I>Sententiarum Libri IV</I>, Lib. IV, dist. xxiv. 8|(Migne, tom. 191, col. 903).</NOTE>/ &thorn;anne bi more strenger resoun&meper; it perteyne&thorn; to a|prest/ For seint Ierom &amp; seint Beede acorden togider &amp; seyn/|Sicut in forma apostolorum est forma episcoporum&meper; ita in septuaginta|duobus discipulis est forma presbiterorum/ Ri&yogh;t as in &thorn;e|apostlis is &thorn;e forme of bischopis&meper; so in &thorn;re score &amp; twelue disciplis.<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="12a">| is &thorn;e forme | of prestis/ But Crist &yogh;aue charge bo&thorn;e to &thorn;ise|bischopis &amp; also to &thorn;ise prestis&meper; &amp; seide/ Mat. x<SUP>o</SUP>.  'Ecce ego|mitto vos'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Matt. x. 16.</NOTE>/ &amp; Luc. x<SUP>o</SUP>. 'Designauit Iesus alios septuaginta duos|&amp; misit illos &amp;c.;'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Luc. x. 1.</NOTE> &Verbar;  Loo I sende &yogh;ou as schepe among wolues &Verbar;|And efte Iesu asigned &thorn;rescore &amp; twelue&meper; &amp; sent hem to preche &Verbar;|How schal &thorn;ise bischopis maynten &thorn;er constituciouns&meper; a&yogh;ens &thorn;er|God &amp; holi seintis/ It schal be more suffurable to Sodom &amp; Gomor&meper;|&thorn;an to &thorn;is peple &thorn;at disturblen Goddis ordinaunce &Verbar;</P>
<P>
<PB N="13">&THORN;e sixt synne is fi&yogh;ting a&yogh;ens &thorn;e tru&thorn;e&meper; &thorn;at a man knowi&thorn;/ &thorn;at|is. whanne &thorn;e tru&thorn;e is tolde to &thorn;e gilti&meper; &thorn;e whiche disposi&thorn; him|not to be amendid/ &thorn;anne he maki&thorn; blynde vngroundid resouns.|wi&thorn; sotil argumentis &amp; foltid sophisticacioun/ &amp; dampne&thorn; &thorn;e|tru&thorn;e a&yogh;ens his conscience&meper; wi&thorn; a boold forheed &thorn;at can not|schame&meper; as &THORN;e prophet Ieromye sei&thorn;. iii<SUP>o</SUP>.  'Frons mulieris meretricis|facta est tibi&meper; &amp; noluisti erubescere'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Jer. iii. 3.</NOTE> &Verbar; A stroumpetis forhed|is made vnto | &thorn;ee&meper; &amp; &thorn;ou woldist not be aschamed/  But as Poul <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="12b">|sei&thorn;. Thimo. iii<SUP>o</SUP>.  'Quemadmodum Iambres &amp; Mambres resistiterunt|Moisi&meper; ita &amp; hij resistent veritati'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. 2 Tim. iii. 8.</NOTE> &Verbar; Ri&yogh;t as Iambres|&amp; Mambres a&yogh;en-stooden Moises in &thorn;e si&yogh;t of Pharo&meper; so &thorn;ise|a&yogh;en-stonden|&thorn;e tru&thorn;e corruptid men in &thorn;er mynde &Verbar; And if &thorn;ou wilt|knowe what &thorn;ise men ben&meper; axe seint Peter &amp; he wole telle &thorn;ee/|for he clepi&thorn; hem bi &thorn;er name in his epistil&meper; where sei&thorn; &Verbar; II. Petir ii<SUP>o</SUP>.|'Magistri mendaces qui introducent sectas perdicionis'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. 2 Pet. ii. 1.</NOTE> &Verbar; Seint|Petir sei&thorn;. &thorn;ise ben maistir liears. &thorn;at schullen bring in among|&thorn;e peple&meper; sectis of perdicioun. &thorn;at is of losse &amp; dee&thorn; &Verbar; &thorn;ou&yogh; &yogh;e rise|wi&thorn; Lucifer&meper; &amp; make &yogh;oure nestis among &thorn;e sterris/ from &thorn;ens &yogh;e|schullen be drawen&meper; &amp; &thorn;rowen to &thorn;e grounde &Verbar;  Whanne wole &yogh;e|marke &thorn;e wordis of Crist&meper; &thorn;at cursi&thorn; &yogh;ou for &yogh;oure apostasie/ &|for &yogh;e pullen as foxis to her hoolis&meper; children from fadris.  Crist sei&thorn;|to &yogh;ou. Mat. xxiii<SUP>o</SUP>. 'Ve vobis scribe et pharisei qui cir-|-cuitis terram <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="13a">|&amp; mare &amp;c.;'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Matt. xxiii. 15 'Vae vobis scribae et pharisaei hypocritae: quia|circuitis mare et aridam,' etc.</NOTE> &Verbar;  Woo to &yogh;ou scribis &amp; pharises ypocritis. &thorn;at|cumpassen aboute &thorn;e see &amp; &thorn;e lond to make &yogh;ou a novise/ &|whanne &yogh;e han founden him. &yogh;e maken him helle broond&meper; double &thorn;an|&yogh;oure silf/ As &thorn;e vnkunnyngnes of Pharoos philosophurs was made|knowen&meper; so &thorn;e fals impunyng of &thorn;e tru&thorn;e. of &thorn;ise sotil ypocritis|schal hastli be made open. &Verbar; Alle men take hede to &thorn;ise sixe|synnes. for &thorn;ei ben cause of batailes. discenciouns. hounger.|pestelence. veniaunce. &amp; of al maner of mischef/ &amp; at &thorn;e laste|&thorn;ise synnes ben cause whi soules ben chaff&meper; as we seide toforne &Verbar;</P>
