<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="8">
<HEAD>Of good and yuel comyng to &thorn;is material chirche.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Capitulum .VIII<SUP>m</SUP>.. &Verbar;</HEAD>
<P>Aftir &thorn;is we schal speke&meper; of twoo dyuerse partise/ &thorn;at comen
<PB N="44">|togidir to &thorn;is chirche&meper; bo&thorn;e of good &amp; yuel/  Firste we taken for|oure grounde&meper; Cristis holi gospel/ where he speki&thorn; in parable&meper;|to hise owene disciplis. Mat. xiii<SUP>o</SUP>. 'Simile est regnum celorum|sagene misse in mare. &amp; ex omni genere piscium congreganti quam|cum impleta esset educentes &amp; secus litus sedentes. elegerunt bonos|in vasa sua malos autem foras miserunt'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Matt. xiii. 47.</NOTE> &Verbar;  &THORN;e rewme of heuenes|is lijk<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. lijf.</NOTE> to a nett&meper; &thorn;at is sent in to &thorn;e see/ &amp; gadri&thorn; to-gidre in<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="42a">| to his cloos&meper; of alle &thorn;e kynde of diuerse fisches/ &amp; | whanne &thorn;is|nett was ful of fisches&meper; &thorn;e fischers drowen it to &thorn;e lond/ &amp; &thorn;ei|sitting biside &thorn;e see-brynk&meper; chosen &thorn;e good in to her vessellis/ &thorn;e|yuel forso&thorn;e &thorn;ei sentten oute&meper; &amp; kesten hem a&yogh;en in to &thorn;e see<NOTE PLACE="foot">W. V. 'The kingdom of heuenes is lic to a nette sent in to the see, and of|alle kynd of fishis gedrynge; the whiche whan it was fulfillid, men ledynge|out, and sittinge bysidis the brynke, cheesiden the good into her vessels, but|thei senten out the yuel.'  1388, 'The kyngdom of heuenes is lijk to a nette|cast into the see, and that gaderith to gidere of al kynde of fisschis; which|whanne it was ful, thei drowen up, and seten bi the brenke, and chesen the|goode in to her vessels, but the yuel thei kesten out.'</NOTE> &Verbar;</P>
<P>&THORN;is parable &thorn;us to mene&meper; aftir &thorn;e witt of Crist Iesu &Verbar;  &THORN;e|secounde chirche here in er&thorn;e&meper; is lijke to a nett sent into &thorn;e see/|for as &thorn;e see ebbi&thorn; &amp; flowi&thorn;&meper; so &thorn;is chirche now rise&thorn; &amp; falli&thorn;/ to|preise &amp; lake as wawis of &thorn;e see&meper; &thorn;at risen feel si&thorn;es ouir menes|mi&yogh;t.  As &thorn;e tempestis of &thorn;e see&meper; ben hidouse &amp; perilouse for &thorn;e|nett/  So pride &thorn;at wawi&thorn; in &thorn;is world&meper; is ful noiouse to Cristis|chirche/  of beaute of fortune of goodis of grace&meper; al dai men|bollen in hi&yogh;enes of herte &Verbar;</P>
<P>&THORN;e see watir is al bittir&meper; &amp; ful sowrische in &thorn;e tasting/ &amp; &thorn;is|world is ful of envie&meper; &thorn;at is ful bittir for to taast wi&thorn; haate as|bittir as &thorn;e soot&meper; &thorn;at noon vnne&thorn; can corde wi&thorn; o&thorn;ir &Verbar;</P>
<P>On &thorn;e see come&thorn; grevouse stormes&meper; wi&thorn; pirwittis &thorn;at greuen|soore/ &amp; in &thorn;is world rise&thorn; wra&thorn;&thorn;e&meper; wi&thorn; hanger of herte &thorn;at|doi&thorn; miche tene/ |<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="42b"></P>
<P>In &thorn;e see no grasse mai growe&meper; nei&thorn;ir as fer as it mai flowe/|but it wasti&thorn; al &thorn;e grounde&meper; &amp; maki&thorn; it nakid wi&thorn;outen fruyte/|And in &thorn;is world is viciouse slou&thorn;e&meper; &thorn;at stroie&thorn; vertues in bodi &|soule/ &amp; maki&thorn; man foltid in hise wittis&meper; in euery parte where|euere he strecche &Verbar;</P>
<P>&THORN;e see euer purchasi&thorn; wi&thorn; hise wawis&meper; &amp; wynne&thorn; of ground|&thorn;at he nei&yogh;e&thorn;/ &amp; is not paied of &thorn;e termes&meper; &thorn;at God ha&thorn; sett if
<PB N="45">|it mi&yogh;t scape/  And in &thorn;is world is couetise&meper; of hem &thorn;at purchasen|wi&thorn; wrong/ her nei&yogh;boris ground &amp; her catel&meper; wi&thorn; sli&yogh; cautels of|mannes lawe &Verbar;  &THORN;us &thorn;ei wynnyn more &amp; more&meper; &amp; wil not wiseli|spende her owene/ nei&thorn;ir &thorn;ank God in dewe forme&meper; til &thorn;ei be|cau&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. cau&yogh;</NOTE> in &thorn;e fendis snare/</P>
<P>&THORN;e see belchi&thorn; miche fil&thorn;e&meper; &amp; casti&thorn; from him foule corrupcioun&meper;|&amp; &thorn;at is ful abhominable&meper; &amp; vgli for man to loke vpon/  And in|&thorn;is world is leccherie&meper; &thorn;at defoule&thorn; bodi &amp; soule/ it turne&thorn; &thorn;e|preciouse temple of God&meper; in to &thorn;e logge of griseli delues/  &THORN;e|peple &thorn;at haunten &thorn;is wrecchid synne&meper; ben mad as beestis wi&thorn;outen|lawe/ &amp; in &thorn;is bestial con-|-dicioun&meper; &thorn;ei fi&yogh;ten as beestis wi&thorn;outen <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="43a">|resoun/ and &thorn;us &thorn;ei welken &amp; dwynen awey&meper; al wlatsumli to God|&amp; man &Verbar;</P>
<P>&THORN;e see feel si&thorn;is wi&thorn; hir greet tempestis&meper; &thorn;at sodenli rise&thorn; to|greet harm/ drowne&thorn; man &amp; also vessells&meper; &amp; leesi&thorn; hem or &thorn;ei|come to lond/  And in &thorn;is world is glotenye&meper; &thorn;at drowne&thorn; &thorn;e|wittis of &thorn;e peple/ til &thorn;at &thorn;ei be vnresonable &amp; kunnen not knowe|whanne &thorn;ei han wrong &Verbar;  Certis excesse of mete &amp; drink&meper; slee&thorn;|many moo &thorn;an doi&thorn; &thorn;e swerid/ for in diuerse metis &amp; drynkis&meper;|greedili taken at a mele/ is noo heele &thorn;e wiseman sei&thorn;&meper; but sijknes|bo&thorn;e to bodi &amp; soule &Verbar;</P>
<P>We must aspiee to flee &thorn;ise perellis&meper; &thorn;at ben in &thorn;is greuouse|see/ &amp; drawe &thorn;is nett in watir of wisdam&meper; bi vertuouse lyuyng to|&thorn;e hauen of hel&thorn;e/ wi&thorn; cordis &thorn;at ben of verry mekenesse&meper; wi&thorn;|pacience &amp; wi&thorn; longabiding/ seiling wi&thorn; loue &amp; charite&meper; in hooli|spede &amp; good occupacioun/ larging oure handis in dedis of mercy&meper;|&thorn;at pore nedi mai be oure bedemen/ leeding oure lijf in discret|mesure&meper; in what &thorn;at we | schal take or leeve/ cladde in clennes <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="43b">|&amp; chastite&meper; &amp; &thorn;anne schal Crist be al oure counfort/  whe&thorn;er|euere we be bi lond or watir&meper; as he ha&thorn; grauntid bi his gospel/|Mat. xxviii<SUP>o</SUP>. 'Ego ero vobiscum vsque ad consummacionem seculi'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Matt. xxviii. 20 'Ego vobiscum sum omnibus diebus, usque ad|consummationem saeculi.'</NOTE> &Verbar;|I schal be wi&thorn; &yogh;ou in wel &amp; woo&meper; til &thorn;is world be brou&yogh;t to an|ende<NOTE PLACE="foot">W. V. 'I am with &yogh;ou in alle dayes til the endyng of the world.'  1388,|'I am with &yogh;ou in alle daies, in to the ende of the world.'</NOTE> &Verbar;</P>
<P>&THORN;e fisches &thorn;at swymmen in &thorn;is see&meper; ben alle &thorn;e peple &thorn;at lyuen
<PB N="46">|in &thorn;is world/ bo&thorn;e good &amp; yuel of euery degree&meper; of iche staate|temperel or spirituel/  But as &thorn;e greet fisches eeten &thorn;e smale&meper; so|mi&yogh;ti riche men of &thorn;is world/ deuouren &thorn;e pore to her bare boon&meper;|eeting &thorn;e moselles &thorn;at hem beest like&thorn;/ as &thorn;e wise man sei&thorn;.|Ecci. xiii<SUP>o</SUP>. 'Venacio leonis onager in heremo&meper; sic pascua diuitum|sunt pauperes'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Ecclesiasticus xiii. 23.</NOTE> &Verbar;  &THORN;e hounting or &thorn;e pray of &thorn;e lioun&meper; is &thorn;e|feelde-asse in wildirnes/ so feding of &thorn;e riche men&meper; ben pore nedi|men/  And whanne &thorn;e sunne schynne&thorn; warme&meper; &amp; in a mylde|wedir/ &thorn;e greet fisches drawen ny&yogh; &thorn;e eire&meper; &amp; driuen doune &thorn;e|smale/ and if &thorn;er come an aile-storm&meper; or a coolde cesoun/ &thorn;ise|greet fisches falle to &thorn;e grounde&meper; &amp; putt abouen &thorn;e smale/  So<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="44a">| whanne | riche men sen a vauntage&meper; or ony worldis wynnyng/|&thorn;ei risen abouen &thorn;e cloudis&meper; in vaunting of her richessis/ &amp; al|tolaken &thorn;e symple comvnes&meper; &amp; seyn '&thorn;ei mai not paie/ wherof|don &thorn;ei entirmetenen hem&meper; &thorn;ei ben but verry beggers'/  But|whanne &thorn;er come&thorn; a charge to &thorn;e countre&meper; as taxis. loones. or ony|o&thorn;ir payment/ &thorn;anne &thorn;e riche men fallen doun&meper; &amp; feynen hem silf|nedi/ &amp; magnifien &thorn;e pore man&meper; &thorn;at wonne&thorn; bisi&yogh;de him/ &amp; sei&thorn;|he is a pryue man&meper; &amp; hidi&thorn; miche richesse &Verbar;  And &thorn;us sei&thorn;|almi&yogh;ti God&meper; bi &thorn;e prophete Abacuk. i<SUP>o</SUP>. 'Facies homines quasi|pisces maris &amp; quasi reptilia non habentia ducem/  Et factum est|iudicium &amp; contradictio potencior/ propter hoc lacerata est lex&meper;|&amp; non peruenit usque ad finem iudicium/ quia impius preualet|iustum propterea egreditur iudicium peruersum'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Hab. i. 14, 3, 4 'Facies homines quasi pisces maris et quasi reptile|non habens principem . . . quia impius praevalet adversus iustum, propterea|egreditur iudicium perversum.'</NOTE> &Verbar;  &THORN;e prophet|seing in his spirit&meper; how riche men wasten &thorn;e pore nedi/ he taki&thorn;|his vois of greet moone&meper; &amp; maki&thorn; his moornyng to his God &Verbar;|Lord schalt &thorn;ou suffre men<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. me.</NOTE> to be mad&meper; as fisches &thorn;at swymmen|in &thorn;e see/ &amp; as if &thorn;ei were creping beestis&meper; &thorn;at han no leeder<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="44b">| here in er&thorn;e/ &amp; iugement is mad | &thorn;e cruelar&meper; &amp; a&yogh;enseiyng &thorn;e|mi&yogh;tiar/ wherfor &thorn;e lawe is al to-torn&meper; &amp; iugement come&thorn; to no|perfi&yogh;te ende/ for now ha&thorn; &thorn;e wickid wreche&meper; mi&yogh;t to ouerecome|&thorn;e ri&yogh;twise man/ &thorn;erfore passi&thorn; for&thorn;e among mankynde&meper; weiward|iugment &thorn;at stroie&thorn; pees<NOTE PLACE="foot">W. V. 'And thou shalt make men as fishis of the se, and as crepyngge|thingis not hauinge duyk, and dom is maad, and a&yogh;einsayinge more mi&yogh;ty.|For this thing law is to-broken, and dom cummeth not unto the eende: for|unpitous man hath mi&yogh;t a&yogh;einus the iust, therfore weywerd dom shal go out.'|1388, 'And thou schalt make men as fischis of the see, and as crepynge thingis|not hauynge a ledere; and doom is maad, and a&yogh;enseiyng is more mi&yogh;ti.  For|this law is to-broken, and doom cometh not til to the ende; for the unpitouse|man hath mi&yogh;t a&yogh;ens the iust, therfor weiward doom schal go out.'</NOTE> &Verbar;</P>
<P>
<PB N="47">But for &thorn;at fisches ben ri&yogh;t quiuer&meper; &amp; quik. in plente of &thorn;e|watir/ &amp; dreden not &thorn;e hidouse wawis&meper; whe&thorn;ir &thorn;ei risen hi&yogh;e or|fallen lowe/ In &thorn;is place &thorn;ei schal bitoken&meper; trewe bileue of mannes|herte/ &amp; to &thorn;is witt speki&thorn; Crist&meper; in &thorn;e gospel &amp; stiri&thorn; vs to preie/|Luk. xi<SUP>o</SUP>.  'Quis autem ex vobis patrem petit piscem&meper; numquid|pro pisce serpentem dabit illi?'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Luc. xi. 11.</NOTE>  Forso&thorn;e sei&thorn; Crist.  whiche of|&yogh;ou axe mi fadir a fishe&meper; whe&thorn;ir schal he &yogh;yue him for &thorn;is fische|an addre?<NOTE PLACE="foot">W. V. 'Who of you axith the fadir fysch, wher he schal &yogh;yue to him|a serpent for the fysch?'</NOTE> naye pleynly &Verbar; Crisostum sei&thorn; vpon &thorn;is tixt&meper; &thorn;at &thorn;is|fische is mannes fei&thorn;/ &amp; aftir &thorn;is we schulden preie&meper; to oure fadir|&thorn;at is in heuene/ &thorn;at he wole stable vs in trewe bileue&meper; &amp; in &thorn;e|articlis &thorn;at longen &thorn;erto/ for &thorn;anne we schal be wel disposid&meper; in|&thorn;e watir of tribulacioun/ to do &amp; suffre as plesi&thorn; God&meper; lyueli|ioieyng | for &thorn;is bileue/ &amp; &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;er seeme perel of dee&thorn;&meper; oure <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="45a">|conscience schal no &thorn;ing abasche/ for socour is kept for alle fei&thorn;ful&meper;|in &thorn;e tresour of Cristis passioun &Verbar;</P>
<P>&THORN;e fischers &thorn;at drawen &thorn;is forseid nett&meper; ben aungelis sent aforn|&thorn;e doome/ &thorn;at schal whi&yogh;tli do Goddis message&meper; and bring alle|folkis in a stounde/ beforn &thorn;e face of God almi&yogh;ti&meper; in to &thorn;e vale|of Iosophat.  Ioelis. iii<SUP>o</SUP>.  'Congregabo omnes gentes &amp; deducam|eas in vallem Iosephat &amp; disceptabo ibi cum eis super populo meo|&amp; hereditate mea Israel'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Joel iii. 2.</NOTE> &Verbar;  &THORN;e Lord God sei&thorn; &thorn;at he schal gaddir|togidir alle folkis&meper; &amp; he schal leede hem in to &thorn;e vale of Iosophat/|&amp; &thorn;ere he schal make wi&thorn; hem&meper; a ri&yogh;twise reckenyng/ vpon hise|peple Israel&meper; &thorn;at is his owene heritage/ and &thorn;anne schal Crist wi&thorn;|hise seintis&meper; departe &thorn;e yuel from &thorn;e good/  Crist chesi&thorn; &thorn;e good|of his chirche&meper; in to &thorn;e vessel of blisse/ but &thorn;e yuel &thorn;ei casten|out&meper; in to &thorn;e chymney of fire/ &thorn;ere schal be weeping for bittirnesse|of smook&meper; and gnasting of tee&thorn; for quaking of coold &Verbar;<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="45b"></P>
