<DIV2 TYPE="chapter" N="12">
<HEAD>Of &thorn;e fendis cautels bi whiche he pursue&thorn; in hise membris&meper; &thorn;e|kepers of Goddis heestis &Verbar;  Capitulum .XII<SUP>m</SUP>.. &Verbar;</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<P>The yuel part of &thorn;is chirche&meper; schal neuer cese/ wi&thorn; &thorn;e malice<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="76b">| &thorn;at &thorn;ei | may&meper; to purswe good lyuars/  But for hise chosen|children&meper; God schal abrege/ &thorn;e daies of her woodnes&meper; &amp; &thorn;at schal
<PB N="81">|men wel knowe/ as seint Ion sei&thorn; to &thorn;e chirche&meper; &amp; &yogh;yue&thorn; it good|counfort/ Apoc. ii<SUP>o</SUP>.  'Nichil horum timeas que passurus es/|Ecce missurus est diabolus ex vobis in carcerem &amp; habebitis|tribulacionem diebus decem. esto fidelis vsque ad mortem &amp; dabo|tibi coronam vite/ qui habet aures audiendi audiat quid spiritus|dicat ecclesijs/ qui vicerit a morte secunda non ledetur'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Apoc. ii. 10, 11 'Nihil horum timeas quae passurus es ... diabolus|aliquos ex vobis in carcerem, ut tentemini, et habebitis ... qui habet|aurem,' etc.</NOTE>/  Drede|&thorn;ou not &thorn;oo &thorn;ingis&meper; &thorn;at &thorn;ou arte for to suffre/ Lo &thorn;e deuel is for|to sende&meper; of &yogh;ou into &thorn;e prisoun/ &amp; &yogh;e schal haue tribulacioun&meper;|ten daies bidene/ Be &thorn;ou fei&thorn;ful to &thorn;e dee&thorn;&meper; &amp; I schal &yogh;yue to &thorn;ee|a croune of lijf/ he &thorn;at ha&thorn; eeris of heering heere he&meper; what &thorn;e|spirit sei&thorn; to &thorn;e chirchis/ who &thorn;at ha&thorn; ouercomen&meper; schal not be|hirt of &thorn;e secounde dee&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">W. V. 'Drede thou no thing of thes whiche thou art to suffringe.  Lo!|the deuel is to sendinge summe of &yogh;ou in to prisoun, that &yogh;e be temptid; and|&yogh;e shulen haue tribulacioun in ten dayes.  Be thou feithful unto the deeth,|and I shal &yogh;iue to thee a coroun of lijf.  He that hath eres, here, what the|spirit shal seie to the chirchis.  He that shal ouercome, shal not be hirt of|the secounde deeth.'</NOTE> &Verbar; vndirstonde &thorn;ou bi &thorn;is deuel&meper; alle &thorn;e|yuel peple/ &thorn;at schal purswe good lyuars&meper; vnto &thorn;e worldis ende/|sumtyme more sumtyme lesse&meper; wi&thorn; diuerse peynes of turmentrie &Verbar;|And vndirstonde &thorn;ou | bi &thorn;ise ten daies&meper; &thorn;e ten comaundementis/ <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="77a">|for &thorn;ei ben ly&yogh;t of mannes witt&meper; in dercknes of &thorn;is world/ as &thorn;e|dai passi&thorn; &thorn;e ny&yogh;t&meper; in his cleer schynyng &Verbar; Of &thorn;ese ten comaundementis&meper;|&thorn;e fende feyne&thorn; his accioun/ to trouble &thorn;e good of &thorn;e|chirche&meper; &amp; sende hem to &thorn;e prisoun/ And here it seme&thorn; spedy&meper;|to telle &thorn;e fendis cautells/ &thorn;at he vsi&thorn; in hise membris&meper; a&yogh;en|Goddis heestis/ &amp; as &thorn;e cloude in &thorn;e dai&meper; so marri&thorn; he mannes|wittis &Verbar;</P></DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="commandment" N="1">
<HEAD>&THORN;e firste heest &Verbar;</HEAD>
<P>The firste heeste of God is &thorn;is. Exo. xx<SUP>o</SUP>. Mat. xxii<SUP>o</SUP>. Mar. xiii<SUP>o</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Ex. xx. 2-6; Matt. xxii. 37; Marc. xii. 29, 30.</NOTE>/|'I am &thorn;e Lord &thorn;i God. &thorn;at haue ledde &thorn;ee out of &thorn;e lond of Egipt|from &thorn;e hous of &thorn;raldom/ bifore me &thorn;ou schalt not haue noon alien|goddis. &thorn;ou schalt make to &thorn;ee no grauen &thorn;ing. nei&thorn;ir ony licknes|of ony &thorn;ing &thorn;at is in heuene aboue.  or in er&thorn;e bine&thorn;. or of &thorn;oo|&thorn;ingis &thorn;at ben in watir vndir-ne&thorn;e. &thorn;ou schalt not worschip hem|ne loute hem &Verbar;  I am &thorn;e Lord &thorn;i God strong loue-gelous. visiting|&thorn;e wickidnes of fadris vpon sones. in to &thorn;e | &thorn;ridde &amp; &thorn;e four&thorn;e <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="77b">
<PB N="82">|generacioun of hem &thorn;at haten me/ &amp; I doing mercy in to &thorn;ousandis.|to hem &thorn;at louen me &amp; kepen myn heestis<NOTE PLACE="foot">W. V. 'Y am the Lord thi God, that hath lad thee out of the loond of|Egipte, fro the hows of thraldom.  Thow shalt not haue alyen goddis before|me.  Thow shalt not mak to thee grauen thing, ne eny licknes that is in|heuene aboue, and that is in erthe benethe, ne of hem that ben in watrys|under erthe; thow shalt not anoure hem, ne herye hem; I forsothe am the|Lord thi God, strong gelows, visitynge the wickidnes of fadris in sones into|the thridde and the ferthe generacioun of hem that hatiden me, and doynge|merci into thousyndes to hem that louen me, and kepen myn heestis.'  1388,|'Y am thi Lord God, that ladde thee out of the lond of Egipt, fro the hous|of seruage.  Thou schalt not haue alien goddis before me.  Thou schalt not|make to thee a grauun ymage. nethir ony licnesse of thing which is in heuene|aboue, and which is in erthe bynethe, nether of tho thingis, that ben in|watris undur erthe: thou schalt not herie tho, nether thou schalt worschipe;|for Y am thi Lord God, a stronge gelouse louyere; and Y visite the wickidnesse|of fadris into the thridde and fourthe generacioun of hem that haten me,|and Y do mercy in to a thousynde, to hem that louen me, and kepen myn|heestis.'</NOTE> &Verbar;</P>
<P>A&yogh;en &thorn;is comaundement&meper; &thorn;e fende ha&thorn; leied twoo snaris/ &amp; in|hem he cacche&thorn; &thorn;e peple&meper; &thorn;at &thorn;ei moun not scape/ but o&thorn;ir &thorn;ey|musten graunt his wille&meper; or elles &thorn;ei schal to prisoun &Verbar;</P>
<P>&THORN;e firste is clepid obedience&meper; &thorn;at &thorn;e fende chalenge&thorn;/ cheueli to|be don to him&meper; or to hise leeftenauntis/ as to prelatis or to|prestis&meper; &thorn;at ben hise officeris/ and asken &thorn;is obedience&meper; what|euer &thorn;ei comaunde/ &thorn;at symple men obeye to hem&meper; in hi&yogh;e &amp; in|lowe &Verbar;  Al &thorn;is world crie&thorn; lowid&meper; aftir &thorn;is obedience/ &amp; seyn|'whateuer &thorn;i souereyn biddi&thorn;&meper; &thorn;ou schalt obeye &thorn;erto' &Verbar;  Here we|graunten of bileue&meper; &thorn;at we owen obedience/ to oure souereyns|&thorn;at techen vs&meper; to knowe God &amp; drede him/ &yogh;he whe&thorn;ir &thorn;at &thorn;ei|ben mynystris&meper; in &thorn;e spiritual part/ or officeris in temperalte&meper;|we must obeye to hem/ in &thorn;at &thorn;at &thorn;ei obei to God&meper; &amp; lerne vs<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="78a">| &thorn;is obedi-|-ence/ for &thorn;us it is writen.  I. Re. xv<SUP>o</SUP>.|'Numquid uult dominus holacausta aut victimas &amp; non pocius vt obediatur|voci domini? melior est enim obediencia quam victime &amp; ascultare|magis quam offerre adipem arietum quoniam quasi peccatum ariolandi|est repugnare &amp; quasi scelus ydolatrie nolle adquiescere.|Pro eo ergo quod abiecisti sermonem domini&meper; abiecit te dominus|ne sis rex'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. 1 Reg. xv. 22, 23.</NOTE>/  Samuel seide to kyng Saule.  No whe&thorn;ir wol &thorn;e|Lord brende offryngis or sacrificis. &amp; not ra&thorn;er &thorn;at it &thorn;e obeied to|&thorn;e vois of &thorn;e Lord? forso&thorn;e obedience is betir &thorn;an sacrificis. &
<PB N="83">|myche betir it is to take hede to &thorn;e lawe&meper; &thorn;an to offre &thorn;e fattnes/|of rames/ for it is as &thorn;e synne of wichcrafte. to fi&yogh;t a&yogh;en God/|&amp; as &thorn;e felonye of ydolatrie&meper; not to consent to Goddis word/  For|&thorn;is cause. &thorn;erfore &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast cast awey &thorn;e worde of &thorn;e Lord&meper; &thorn;e|Lord ha&thorn; cast &thorn;e awey.  &thorn;at &thorn;ou be not kyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">W. V. 'Whether wole the Lord brent sacrifices or slayn offryngis and|not more that it be obeishid to the voice of the Lord?  Forsothe betre is|obeishaunce than slayn sacrificis, and to take heed more than to offre the|fatnes of wetheris; for as synne of denyynge bi deuelis is to repugne and as|hidows trespas of mawmetrye to wiln not assent.  Forthi thanne that thow|hast throwen awey the word of the Lord, the Lord hath throwen awey thee,|that thow be not kyng.'  1388, 'Whether the Lord wole brent sacrifices,|ethir slayn sacrifices and not more that me obeie to the vois of the Lord?|For obedience is betere than sacrifices, and to herkene Goddis word is more|than to offre the ynnere fatnesse of rammes; for it is as the synne of|mawmetrie to fi&yogh;te a&yogh;ens Goddis heest, and it is as the wickidnesse of ydolatrie|to nyle ascente to Goddis heest.  Therfor for that, that thou castidest awey|the word of the Lord, the Lord castide thee awei, that thou be not kyng.'</NOTE> &Verbar; and to &thorn;is &thorn;e|wise man acordi&thorn; &amp; sei&thorn;. Ecci. iiii<SUP>o</SUP>. 'Multo enim melior est obediencia|quam stultorum victime. qui nesciunt quid faciunt mali'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Eccles. iv. 17.</NOTE>/|&thorn;at is to seye. | Miche betir is obedience &thorn;an sacrifice of foolis&meper; <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="78b">|for yuel folkis wot not what &thorn;ei do<NOTE PLACE="foot">W. V. 'Myche betere is obeisaunce than victori sacrifises of foolis, that|wite not what thei don of yuel.'  1388, 'Myche betere is obedience than the|sacrifices of foolis, that witen not what yuel thei don.'</NOTE> &Verbar;  And seint Poul techi&thorn; an|open rule&meper; of &thorn;is maner obedience&meper; wi&thorn; &thorn;e cause of souerente&meper;|&amp; knitti&thorn; hem bo&thorn;e togiddir/ Heb. vlti<SUP>o</SUP>. 'Obedite prepositis|vestris &amp; subiacete eis. ipsi enim peruigilant quasi rationem pro|animabus vestris reddituri'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Heb. xiii. 17.</NOTE>/ &thorn;at is to seie.  Obeie &yogh;e to &yogh;oure|souereyns&meper; &amp; vndirloute &yogh;e to hem/ &amp; cause whi is &thorn;is. forso&thorn;e|&thorn;ei walken perfi&yogh;tli. as for to &yogh;elde a reckenyng for &yogh;oure soulis<NOTE PLACE="foot">W. V. 'Obeye &yogh;e to &yogh;oure prouostis, (or prelatis), and undirligge to hem;|thei perfytly waken, asto &yogh;eldinge resoun for &yogh;oure soulis.'  1388, 'Obeie &yogh;e|to &yogh;oure souereyns, and be &yogh;e suget to hem; for thei perfitli waken, as to|&yogh;eldinge resoun for &yogh;oure soulis.'</NOTE> &Verbar;|If &thorn;is cause be taken awey&meper; obedience cesi&thorn; &thorn;ere also/ as &thorn;e|philosophur sei&thorn; 'Cessante causa&meper; cessabit officialis'/ whanne &thorn;e|cause cesi&thorn;&meper; &thorn;e spede &thorn;erof schal cese &Verbar;  But seint Petir techi&thorn;|obedience&meper; &thorn;at we schal do to lordis/ &amp; &thorn;at in more larger|maner&meper; &thorn;an we owen to &thorn;e clergie. I. Pe. ii<SUP>o</SUP>. &Verbar; 'Serui subdite|estote in omni timore dominis. non tantum bonis &amp; modestis. sed
<PB N="84">|etiam discolis'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. 1 Pet. ii. 18.</NOTE>/ &thorn;at is to seie.  Seruauntis be &yogh;e suget in al|drede to &yogh;oure temperal lordis/ &amp; not oonli to good &amp; to esy lordis.<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="79a">| &thorn;at is to seie. in loue. but | also to tyrauntis. &thorn;at is to seie. in|pacience/  But fendis lymes feynen hem&meper; to be on Cristis si&yogh;de/|&amp; to do correcciouns&meper; aftir Cristis wille/ &amp; seyn &thorn;ei aske obedience&meper;|to amende soulis/ whanne &thorn;ei do &thorn;is &thorn;ing in dede&meper; &thorn;at &thorn;ei|here speken/ &thorn;anne we schal obeie to hem&meper; &amp; ellis we schal|answere/ as Petir seide to bischopis&meper; &amp; prestis of &thorn;e lawe/|Act. v<SUP>o</SUP>./ 'Obedire oportet deo magis quam hominibus'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Act. v. 29.</NOTE> &Verbar;  It|bihoue&thorn; more to obeie to God&meper; &thorn;an to men/ Seint Ierom sei&thorn;.|If &thorn;e prelat or &thorn;e lord&meper; bidde ony &thorn;ink/ &thorn;at accordi&thorn; to Goddis|wille&meper; obeie &thorn;ou &thorn;anne to hem/ If &thorn;ei bidde &thorn;e contrarie&meper; to|God &amp; to his lawe/ &thorn;anne seie &thorn;us.  I must ra&thorn;er obeie to &thorn;e lord|of &thorn;e soule&meper; &thorn;an to &thorn;e lord of &thorn;e bodi/ for Crist sei&thorn;.  Mat. x<SUP>o</SUP>.|Luk xii<SUP>o</SUP>. 'Nolite timere eos qui occidunt corpus animam autem|non possunt occidere sed pocius timete eum qui potest animam &|corpus perdere in gehennam<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Matt. x. 28.</NOTE>/ Ita dico vobis hunc timete'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Luc. xii. 5.</NOTE>/ &thorn;at|is to seie.  Nile &yogh;e drede hem &thorn;at slen &thorn;e bodi&meper; forso&thorn;e &thorn;ei may|not slee &thorn;e soule/ but ra&thorn;er dredi&thorn; him. &thorn;at mai lese bo&thorn;e bodi<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="79b">| &amp; soule&meper; in to &thorn;e pitt of helle/ &thorn;us I | seie to &yogh;ou&meper; drede &yogh;e him/|and seint<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. sein.</NOTE> Gregor sei&thorn;. &thorn;is forseide rule of obedience&meper; schal be|strei&yogh;tli kept/ in children to her parentis&meper; in seruauntis to her|lordis/ in clerkis to her maistris&meper; in prestis to her prelatis &Verbar;|And if we passe &thorn;is rule&meper; in doing of obedience/ &thorn;anne we ben|vnbuxum to God&meper; &amp; folowars of Lucifer &Verbar;</P>
<P>&THORN;e secounde trappe of &thorn;e fende&meper; is clepid pilgrimage/  But|miche ra&thorn;er it schulde be seide&meper; &thorn;e outrage of folis/ for pilgrimage|in due forme&meper; is euere-more good &Verbar; &THORN;e peyntour maki&thorn; an ymage&meper;|forgid wi&thorn; diuerse colours/ til it seme in foolis i&yogh;en&meper; as a lyueli|creature &Verbar; &THORN;is is sett in &thorn;e chirche&meper; in a solempne place/ fast|bounden wi&thorn; boondis&meper; for it schulde not falle/ Prestis of &thorn;e|temple&meper; bigilen &thorn;e peple/ wi&thorn; &thorn;e foule synne of Balaam&meper; in her|open preching &Verbar; &THORN;ei seyn &thorn;at Goddis powere&meper; in worching of hise|miraclis/ lowe&thorn; doun in oo ymage&meper; more &thorn;an in ano&thorn;ir/ &amp; &thorn;erfore|cum &amp; offre to &thorn;is&meper; for here is schewid miche vertu &Verbar; Lord hou<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="80a">| dar &thorn;ise fendis for drede | &thorn;us blasfem her God/ &amp; vse &thorn;e synne
<PB N="85">|of Palaam&meper; &thorn;at Goddis lawe ha&thorn; dampned/ si&thorn;en Crist &amp; hise|seyntis&meper; forsoke &thorn;is worldis wel&thorn;e/ &amp; lyueden a pore lijf&meper; as oure|bileue techi&thorn;/ whi gedre &yogh;e prestis richesses&meper; bi &yogh;oure peyntid|ymages/ to make &yogh;oure silf worldli riche&meper; in spoiling of &thorn;e peple?|And &yogh;it &yogh;e do miche werre&meper; &amp; &thorn;at is knowen in parti/ for bo&thorn;e|&yogh;e &amp; &yogh;oure consentours&meper; &thorn;us doyng ben verry ydolatreris/ as|seint Poul sei&thorn;. Rom. i<SUP>o</SUP>. 'Dicentes se esse sapientes stulti facti|sunt &amp; mutauerunt gloriam incorruptibilis dei in similitudinem|ymaginis corruptibilis hominis'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Rom. i. 22, 23.</NOTE> &Verbar; &THORN;at is to seie. &THORN;is peple seiyng|hem silf to be wijs&meper; &thorn;ei ben made foolis/ for &thorn;ei han chaungid &thorn;e|glorie of God&meper; &thorn;at mai not be defoulid/ in to &thorn;e licknes of mannes|ymage&meper; &thorn;at mai be defoilid<NOTE PLACE="foot">W. V. 'Sothli thei seynge hem selue for to be wyse men ben maad foolis.|And thei chaungiden the glorie of God uncorruptible, (that may not deie, ne|be peirid) in to the lyknesse of an ymage of coruptible man.'  1388, 'For|thei seiynge that that hem silf weren wise, thei weren maad foo is.  And thei|chaungiden the glorie of God uncorruptible in to the licnesse of an ymage of|a deedli man.'</NOTE>/ as Poul sei&thorn;. whanne &thorn;ei knewe|&thorn;e ri&yogh;twisenes of God&meper; &thorn;ei wolde not vndirstande/ &thorn;at &thorn;ei &thorn;at|don suche &thorn;ingis&meper; ben wor&thorn;i &thorn;e dee&thorn;/ Not oonli &thorn;e doars&meper; but|also &thorn;ei &thorn;at consenten | to &thorn;e yuel doars/  For God sei&thorn;. &thorn;ou <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="80b">|schalt nei&thorn;ir worschip hem ne loute hem/ for &thorn;ou schalt|nei&thorn;ir do sacrifice to ymage&meper; ne offryng/ &amp; &thorn;at mene&thorn; God|whanne he sei&thorn;&meper; &thorn;ou schalt not worschip hem. wi&thorn; no godli|worschip/ but &thorn;at &thorn;ei be treweli peyntid&meper; as ny&yogh; as man may/|to brynge to mynde as Gregor sei&thorn;&meper; &thorn;e passioun of Iesu Crist/ &|martirdam of seyntis&meper; as lewid mennes bookis &Verbar;  But seint Austin|sei&thorn;. vpon al wise &thorn;ei han discerued to erre&meper; &thorn;at seeken God &|hise seyntis/ not in bookis&meper; but in peyntid wowis sei&thorn; seint|Austin &Verbar; &THORN;ou schalt not vowe to &thorn;ise ymagis&meper; &thorn;ou schalt not seke|&thorn;ise ymagis/ &thorn;ou schalt not swere bi hem. nei&thorn;ir knele to hem.|ne kisse hem/ nei&thorn;ir putt fei&thorn; hope ne trist in oo ymage&meper; more|&thorn;an in ano&thorn;ir/ and &thorn;us mene&thorn; God whanne he sei&thorn;&meper; &thorn;ou schalt|not loute hem |</P>
<P>But trewe pilgrimage&meper; is don on sixe maneres &Verbar;  Firste we|ben pilgrimes&meper; whanne &thorn;at we ben born/ as &thorn;e comune glose|sei&thorn;&meper; vpon Genesis &Verbar; 'Omnis ciuis patrie celestis per-|-egrinus <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="81a">|est mundi toto tempore vite presentis/'  Euery citizen of &thorn;e|heuenli countre&meper; is a pilgrime of &thorn;is world. for al tyme of &thorn;is
<PB N="86">|present lijf/  And whanne we traueilen sore&meper; to kepe Goddis|heestis/ &thorn;anne we done oure pilgrimage&meper; as &thorn;e prophete sei&thorn;/|Ps. cxviii. 'Cantabiles michi erant iustificaciones tue in loco|peregrinacionis me'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Ps. cxviii. 54.</NOTE> &Verbar;  Lord &thorn;i comaundementis weren my|songis&meper; in tyme of my pilgrimage<NOTE PLACE="foot">W. V. 'Chauntable weren to me thi iustefiyngus: in the place of my|pilgrimaging.'  1388, 'Thi iustifiyngis weren delitable to me to be sungen:|in the place of my pilgrimage.'</NOTE> &Verbar;</P>
<P>&THORN;e secounde tyme we ben pilgrimes&meper; whanne we gon to chirche/|as it is writen. Luk. xxiiii<SUP>o</SUP>./ 'Tu solus peregrinus es in Ierusalem|&amp;c'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Luc. xxiv. 18.</NOTE>/ whanne we don in &thorn;e chirche&meper; in forme as God ha&thorn; tau&yogh;t|vs/ &thorn;anne we do oure pilgrimage&meper; for &thorn;us sei&thorn; seint Luk/|Lucas. ii<SUP>o</SUP>. 'Cum factus esset Iesu annorum. xii. &amp;c.;'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Luc. ii. 42.</NOTE>/</P>
<P>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde tyme we ben pilgrimes&meper; whanne we visiten &thorn;e nedi/|&amp; whanne we delen almes-dede&meper; we don oure pilgrimage/ Luk.|xiiii<SUP>o</SUP>. 'Exi cito in plateas &amp; vicos ciuitatis &amp; pauperes ac debiles|cecos &amp; claudos introduc huc'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Luc. xiv. 21.</NOTE>/  Go &thorn;ou for&thorn;e anoon&meper; in to<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="81b">| stretis &amp; weies &amp; bring in to &thorn;in hous/ &thorn;ise &thorn;re | maner of peple&meper;|pore feble. pore blynde. &amp; pore crokid<NOTE PLACE="foot">W. V. 'Go out soone in to grete stretis and smale streetis of the citee,|and brynge in hidur pore men, and feble, and blynde, and crokid.'  1388,|'Go out swithe in to the grete stretis and smal stretis of the citee, and brynge|ynne hidir pore men, and feble, blynde, and crokid.'</NOTE> &Verbar;</P>
<P>&THORN;e four&thorn;e tyme prestis ben pilgrimes&meper; &thorn;at studien holi writ/|til &thorn;ei haue plente in her mynde&meper; of &thorn;is heuenli wisdam/ and|&thorn;anne &thorn;ei hi&yogh;en hem fast aboute&meper; in al &thorn;e brood world/ to dele|&thorn;is goostli tresour&meper; among &thorn;is witles peple/ &thorn;at is in poynt to|spille for hunger&meper; in wanting goostli teching/ as it is writen.|III. Ion. Karissime fideliter agis quicquid operaris in fratres &|hoc in peregrinos'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. 3 Joh. i. 5 'Charissime, fideliter facis,' etc.</NOTE> &Verbar;  Dere frende &thorn;ou doist fei&thorn;fulli&meper; what euer|&thorn;ou doist to oure bri&thorn;eren/ &amp; namli in to pilgrimes<NOTE PLACE="foot">W. V. 'Moost dere, thou doist feithfully, what euer thou werchist in to|britheren, and this thing in to pilgrimys.'  1388, 'Most dere brother, thou|doist feithfuli, what euer thou worchist in britheren, and that in to pilgrymys.'</NOTE>&meper; &thorn;at prechen|&thorn;e gospel/ &amp; ben apaied where &thorn;ei cum&meper; wi&thorn; pore symple lyulood&Verbar;|</P>
<P>&THORN;e fif&thorn;e tyme &thorn;o ben pilgrimes&meper; &thorn;at wonnen in a toune/ where
<PB N="87">|is no&thorn;ir prest ne lord&meper; to teche hem ne to rule hem/ and &thorn;anne|&thorn;ei gon vnto &thorn;e place&meper; where &thorn;ei may be tau&yogh;t/ &amp; rulid vndir|gouerneaunce&meper; &thorn;is is her<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &thorn;is is is her.</NOTE> pilgrimage/ as it is writen Genesis. xii<SUP>o</SUP>.|xx<SUP>o</SUP>. &amp; xxvi<SUP>o</SUP>.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Gen. xii. 4-9, xx. 1, xxvi. 17.</NOTE>  &THORN;er is non o&thorn;ir pilgrimage&meper; &thorn;at mai plese God/|outtake &thorn;is &thorn;at we haue seide&meper; al holi writ beri&thorn; witnes/ |  For <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="82a">|whanne &thorn;e bodi is leide in graue&meper; &amp; &thorn;e soule for&thorn;e passid/|to blisse o&thorn;ir peyne whe&thorn;ir &thorn;at it be&meper; &thorn;anne &thorn;e sixte is|ended &Verbar;</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="commandment" N="2">
<HEAD>&THORN;e .II. heest &Verbar;</HEAD>
<P>&THORN;e secounde comaundement of God is &thorn;is.  Exo. xx<SUP>o</SUP>. 'Non|assumes nomen dei tui in uanum. nec enim habebit dominus|insontem eum&meper; qui assumpserit nomen dei sui frustra'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Ex. xx. 7.</NOTE>/ &thorn;at is|to seie. &thorn;ou schalt not take &thorn;e name of &thorn;i God in veyn/ forso&thorn;e|&thorn;e Lord schal not haue him clene&meper; &thorn;at ha&thorn; taken &thorn;e name of|God in veyn<NOTE PLACE="foot">W. V. 'Thou schalt not tak the name of the Lord thi God in veyn, ne|forsothe the Lord shal haue innocent hym, that takith the name of the Lord|his God in ydel.'  1388, 'Thou schalt not take in veyn the name of thi Lord|God, for the Lord schal not have hym giltles, that takith in veyn the name of|his Lord God.'</NOTE>/ and Crist sei&thorn; in his gospel.  Mat. v<SUP>o</SUP>./ 'Ego|autem dico uobis non iurare omnino.  neque per celum quia|thronus dei est/ neque per terram. quia scabellum pedum eius est/|neque per Ierusalem. quia ciuitas est regis magni/ neque per|caput<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. capud.</NOTE> tuum iuraueris. quia non potes vnum capillum album facere|aut nigrum/ Sit autem sermo uester. est est. non non'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Matt. v. 34-6.</NOTE> &Verbar;  Forso&thorn;e|I seie to &yogh;ou&meper; not swere on ony wise/ nei&thorn;ir bi heuene&meper; for|it is &thorn;e trone of God/ nei&thorn;ir bi &thorn;e er&thorn;e&meper; for it is &thorn;e stool of his|feet/ nei&thorn;ir bi Ierusalem&meper; for it is &thorn;e cite of a greet kyng/|nei&thorn;ir bi &thorn;i heed&meper; for | &thorn;ou maist not make a heer whi&yogh;t or blak/ <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="82b">|forso&thorn;e be &yogh;oure worde &yogh;he &yogh;he nay nay&meper; wi&thorn; herte &amp; mou&thorn;e|acording<NOTE PLACE="foot">W. V. 'Forsothe Y say to &yogh;ou, to nat swere on al manere: neither by|heuene, for it is the trone of God; nether by the erthe, for it is the stole of|his feet; neither by Jerusalem, for it is the citee of a greet kyng; neither|thou shalt swere by thin heued, for thou maist not make oon heer whyt, or|blak; but be &yogh;oure word &yogh;ea, &yogh;ea; nay, nay.'</NOTE> &Verbar;</P>
<P>
<PB N="88">A&yogh;en &thorn;is comaundement&meper; &thorn;e deuel in hise membris/ constreynen|men for to swere&meper; &amp; leie her hand on bookis/ &amp; &thorn;anne he putti&thorn;|hem to open schame&meper; &amp; if &thorn;ei leeue his bidding/ he sei&thorn; bi lawe|&thorn;ei ben relaps&meper; &amp; &thorn;anne &thorn;ei schal be brent/  And &thorn;is is an|hidouse cloude&meper; vpon &thorn;is schynful dai/ to peyne men for keping|of Goddis comaundement/ for seynt Austin sei&thorn; vpon &thorn;e gospel.|'Christus quod perfectus est docuit. quod infirmitatis est indulsit/|quod supersticiosum est resecauit.  perfeccionis est non iurare|omnino/  infirmitatis iurare conpulsi sed supersticionis iurare|inaniter' Hec Augustinus om. 6/ &thorn;at is to seie. Crist ha&thorn; tau&yogh;t|&thorn;at &thorn;ing&meper; &thorn;at is more perfi&yogh;t/ &thorn;at &thorn;ing &thorn;at is of infirmite&meper; he|ha&thorn; suffrid/ &thorn;at &thorn;ing &thorn;at is supersticiouse&meper; he ha&thorn; kitte awey &Verbar;|It is of perfeccioun&meper; not to swere in ony manere/ It is of infirmite&meper;|to swere constreyned/ but it is of supersticioun&meper; to swere veynli/<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="83a">| for &thorn;e vise man | sei&thorn;&meper; Sap. xiiii<SUP>o</SUP>. 'Non enim iuramentum|est virtus sed peccancium pena perambulat semper iniustorum preuaricacionem'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Sap. xiv. 31 'Non enim iuratorum virtus,' etc.</NOTE>/|&THORN;at is to seie. Sweryng is no vertu&meper; but peyne|of synnars<NOTE PLACE="foot">W. V. 'Forsothe of men swerende is not vertue, but the peyne of|synneres.'  1388, 'Forwhi an ooth is not vertu, but the peyne of synneris.'</NOTE>/ ei&thorn;ir of hem &thorn;at wole not &yogh;yue credence&meper; but if men|swere/ or ellis of hem&meper; &thorn;at sweren wi&thorn;outen cause/ and &thorn;erfore|seint Ion Crisostom&meper;<NOTE PLACE="foot">S. Ioan. Chrysostomus, <I>Homilia XII (Opera</I>, ed. 1547, tom. ii, col. 819).</NOTE> blame&thorn; prestis/ for &thorn;ei bringen for&thorn;e|bookis&meper; to compelle &thorn;e peple for to swere on hem&meper; &amp; aski&thorn; &thorn;is|questioun &Verbar; whe&thorn;ir is not he &thorn;at setti&thorn; an hous on brennyng. gilti|of &thorn;is brennyng? whe&thorn;ir is not he &thorn;at bringi&thorn; a swerid. wi&thorn; whiche|manslau&yogh;tir is don&meper; gilti of &thorn;is manslau&yogh;tir?  So &thorn;ei &thorn;at bryngen|for&thorn;e bookis. on whiche men forsweren hem&meper; ben gilti of &thorn;is forswering/|and he sei&thorn;. If &thorn;is peple wil seie &thorn;e so&thorn;e wi&thorn;outen ony|oo&thorn;&meper; wherto schulde &thorn;ei swere/ &amp; if &thorn;ei suppose &thorn;ei wole seie|fals&meper; whi schulde &thorn;ei compelle hem to forswere hem? &amp; so &thorn;e|greetnesse of synne&meper; stondi&thorn; cheeuli in suche ordinarijs/ ei&thorn;ir|seculere or spirituel&meper; as &thorn;is doctour proue&thorn;/ not accepting purgacioun&meper;<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="83b">| wi&thorn;outen suche oo&thorn;is | and of &thorn;is sweryng come&thorn; wickidnes&meper;|and Goddis greuouse veniaunce/ as &thorn;e wise man sei&thorn;. Eccles.|xxiii<SUP>o</SUP>. 'Vir multum iurans implebitur iniquitate&meper; &amp; a domo eius
<PB N="89">|non discedet plaga'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Ecclesiasticus xxiii. 12.</NOTE>/ &thorn;at is to seie.  A man miche swering schal|be fillid of wickidnes&meper; &amp; veniaunce schal not go from his hous &Verbar;|&yogh;it enemyes purswen a&yogh;en &thorn;is comaundement/ &amp; seyn &thorn;at Crist|him silf swore&meper; &amp; hise seintis bo&thorn;e/ swere bi &thorn;is book &thorn;ou|obstinat man&meper; or ellis &thorn;ou schalt to prisoun/ &THORN;ou schalt swere in|oure courte&meper; bicause of &thorn;in infirmite/ as seint Austin ha&thorn; tau&yogh;t&meper;|whanne &thorn;ou art constreyned<NOTE PLACE="foot">Augustinus, <I>De Sermone Domini</I>, Lib. I, c. 30; Gratian, <I>Decreti</I> Pars|Secunda, causa xxii, quaest. i, cap. v (Migne, tom. 187, col. 1123).</NOTE> &Verbar; To &thorn;is we seyn &thorn;at Iesu Crist&meper;|forbedi&thorn; on alwise swering/ bi ony of &thorn;ise foure &thorn;ingis&meper; &thorn;at he|him silf rehersi&thorn;/ &thorn;at is to seie. heuene or er&thorn;e&meper; ei&thorn;ir bi Ierusalem|or bi &thorn;in owene heed &Verbar;  And whanne &thorn;ise foure ben outaken&meper; wi&thorn;|al &thorn;at is in hem/ &yogh;e schal not grounde &yogh;oure viciouse sweryng&meper;|til &thorn;at heuene be fallen &Verbar;  To &thorn;is &thorn;at seint Austin sei&thorn;&meper; &thorn;ou|schalt swere compellida/ we graunten wel aforne a iugge&meper; if ellis|men wollen not tro-|-we vs &Verbar;  But nei&thorn;ir on bookis schullen we <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="84a">|swere&meper; nei&thorn;ir bi Goddis creaturis/ but aftir &thorn;e forme &thorn;at God|ha&thorn; tau&yogh;t&meper; bi Ieremye &thorn;e prophet/ Iere. iiii<SUP>o</SUP>. 'Iurabis viuit|dominus in veritate &amp; in iudicio &amp; in iusticia'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Jer. iv. 2.</NOTE> &Verbar;  &THORN;at is to seie.|&THORN;ou schalt swere&meper; &thorn;e Lord lyue&thorn;.  in trou&thorn;e &amp; in doome &amp; in|ri&yogh;twisenesse &Verbar; &THORN;e Lord lyue&thorn;. is to mene bi God. or bi &thorn;in holidom.|or bi &thorn;i trow&thorn;e &Verbar;  &THORN;is schalt &thorn;ou not swere&meper; but wi&thorn; &thorn;re condiciouns&Verbar;| &THORN;e firste is trou&thorn;e in &thorn;e conscience of him &thorn;at|sweri&thorn;&meper; wi&thorn;outen ony gile &Verbar;  &THORN;e secounde &thorn;at it be in dom&meper;|to exclude al maner of idel &amp; veyn sweryng &Verbar;  &THORN;e &thorn;ridde. &thorn;at|it be in ri&yogh;twisenes &amp; in no maner disceyte&meper; ne hyndring|to oure nei&yogh;bour. ne discording fro &thorn;e ri&yogh;twisenes of God &Verbar;|But we mai in no case swere bi bookis&meper; as we han seide|aforne/ nei&thorn;ir bi lyueli creaturis&meper; as bi seyntis or ony suche|o&thorn;ir &Verbar;  For &thorn;e wise man sei&thorn;. Ecclesi. xxiii<SUP>o</SUP>. 'Nominibus sanctorum|non assuescas os tuum'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Ecclesiasticus xxiii. 9, 10 'Iurationi non assuescas os tuum ...|nominatio vero Dei non sit assidua in ore tuo, et nominibus sanctorum non|admiscearis.'</NOTE> &Verbar;  &THORN;at is to seie. Custum &thorn;ou not|&thorn;i mou&thorn;&meper; to sweryng bi names of seyntis/ for Crisostom sei&thorn;.
<PB N="90"><MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="84b"> om. 12. 'Qui iurat per creaturam committit ydolatriam'&Verbar; | Iterum.|'qui iurat per creaturas. duppliciter peccat &amp; si iurare liceret.|primo. quia iurat/ secundo quia deificat/ quia quicquid est per|quod quis iurat deificat illud'<NOTE PLACE="foot">S. Ioan. Chrysostomus,<I> Homilia XII (Opera</I>, ed. 1547, tom. ii, col. 819).</NOTE> &Verbar;  &THORN;at is to seie.  He &thorn;at sweri&thorn;|bi a creature&meper; doi&thorn; ydolatrie/ he &thorn;at sweri&thorn; bi creatures&meper; synne&thorn;|duble foold/ &yogh;he &thorn;ou&yogh; it were so&meper; &thorn;at sweryng leeful/ oones. for he|sweri&thorn;/ ano&thorn;ir tyme. for he maki&thorn; him a fals god/ for what euer|it be &thorn;at a man sweri&thorn; bi&meper; &thorn;at &thorn;ing he maki&thorn; his god &Verbar;  Lord hou|manye men &amp; wymmen&meper; maken hem fals goddis/ si&thorn;en wel ny&yogh;|al &thorn;is world ha&thorn; in custum&meper; to swere bi oo seynt or bi o&thorn;ir/|Certis &thorn;ise forseide enemyes ben cheef cause&meper; of suche blasfemouse|sweryng/ what wi&thorn; her sclaundris&meper; &amp; sumtyme wi&thorn; sore punysching/|&amp; freel peple kunnen not stonde&meper; but &yogh;elden hem to &thorn;ise|fendis tempting &Verbar;</P></DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="commandment" N="3">
<HEAD>&THORN;e .III. heest/</HEAD>
<P>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde comaundement of God is &thorn;is. Exodi. xx<SUP>o</SUP>. 'Memento|vt diem sabbati sanctifices. vi. diebus operaberis &amp; facies opera|tua. septimo autem die sabbati domini dei tui est.  Non facies<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="85a">| omne opus tu &amp; filius tuus &amp; filia tua &amp; seruus tuus et | ancilla|tua iumentum tuum &amp; aduena qui est intra portas tuas. vi. diebus|fecit deus celum &amp; terram &amp; mare &amp; omnia que in eis sunt. &|requieuit in die septimo/ Iccirco benedixit deus diei sabbati &|sanctificauit illud'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Ex. xx. 8-11 'Memento ... facies omnia opera tua ... Non|facies omne opus in eo, tu et filius tuus ... Sex enim diebus,' etc.</NOTE>/ &THORN;at is to seie.  Haue mynde &thorn;at &thorn;ou halowe|&thorn;in halidai.  In .vi. daies &thorn;ou schalt worche&meper; &amp; do alle &thorn;in owne|werkis/ forso&thorn;e &thorn;e seuen&thorn;e dai. is &thorn;e sabot of &thorn;i Lord. &thorn;ou schalt|not do ony seruyle werk/ &thorn;ise .vi. schal kepe &thorn;is holidai/ &thorn;i sone|&amp; &thorn;i dou&yogh;ter/ &thorn;i seruaunt &amp; &thorn;in handmayde/ &thorn;i beest &amp; &thorn;i|straunger &thorn;at is wi&thorn;ynne &thorn;i &yogh;atis &Verbar;  In .vi. daies God mad heuene|&amp; er&thorn;e &amp; &thorn;e see. &amp; alle &thorn;ingis &thorn;at ben in hem&meper; &amp; he restid in &thorn;e|seuen&thorn;e dai/ &thorn;erfore God blessid &thorn;e dai of &thorn;e saboth&meper; &amp; made it holi<NOTE PLACE="foot">W. V. 'Haue mynde to halwe thin holy day; sixe daies thow shalt|worche and doon alle thi werkis; the seuenthe forsothe dai is the haliday of|the Lord thi God; thow shalt not doon al werk, thow, and thi sone, and thi|dow&yogh;ter, and thi seruaunt, and thin handmayden thi beeste, and comlyng|that is with ynne thi &yogh;atis; sixe forsothe daies God made heuene and erthe,|the see, and alle thingis that ben in hem, and he restide the seuenthe day;|therfore the Lord blisside to the holiday and halwide it.'  1388, 'Haue thou|mynde, that thou halowe the dai of the sabat; in sixe daies thou schalt|worche and schalt do alle thi werkis; forsothe in the seuenthe day is the|sabat of thi Lord God; thou schalt not do ony werk, thou, and thi sone, and|thi dou&yogh;tir, and thi seruaunt, and thin handmaide, thi werk beest, and the|comelyng which is withynne thi &yogh;atis; for in sixe dayes God made heuene|and erthe, the see, and alle thingis that ben in tho, and restide in the seuenthe|dai; herfor the Lord blesside the dai of the sabat, and halewide it.'</NOTE>/</P>
