<P>Of &thorn;e firste speki&thorn; seint Ion &amp; sei&thorn;.  I. Icn. iii<SUP>o</SUP>.  'Qui odit|fratrem suum homicida est'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. 1 Joh. iii. 15.</NOTE>/  He &thorn;at hati&thorn; his bro&thorn;er&meper; is a|manslear<NOTE PLACE="foot">W. V. 'Ech man that haatith his brother is a manqueller.'  1388,|'Ech man that hatith his brother, is a man sleere.'</NOTE> &Verbar; Summe haten synne in man&meper; &amp; &thorn;is is a perfite hate/|Ps. cxviii.  'Perfecto odio oderam illos &amp;c'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Ps. cxxxviii. 22.</NOTE> &Verbar; Summe haten vertu|in man&meper; &amp; &thorn;ey ben mensleers/ for who &thorn;at sei&thorn; he loue&thorn; his God&meper;|&amp; hati&thorn; &thorn;us his bro&thorn;ir/ he is a lieer&meper; &amp; &thorn;er is no trou&thorn;e in him &Verbar;</P>
<P>Of &thorn;e secounde speki&thorn; &thorn;e prophete &amp; sei&thorn;. Ps. xiii. 'Quorum|os maledictione &amp;c'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Ps. xiii. 3.</NOTE> &Verbar; &THORN;e mou&thorn;e of bakbiters&meper; is ful of cursidnes &|bittirnes/ &amp; her feet ben swift&meper; to scheed out blood<NOTE PLACE="foot">W. V. 'Whos mouth of cursing and bitterness is ful; swifte the feet of|hem to sheden out blod.'  1388, 'Whos mouth is ful of cursyng and bittirnesse;|her feet ben swift to schede out blood.'</NOTE>/ for seint|Bernard sei&thorn;.  &THORN;e bakbiter &amp; &thorn;e wilful heerer&meper; ei&thorn;ir of hem<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. of he.</NOTE>|beri&thorn; &thorn;e deuel in her tung/ And &thorn;is bakbiter slee&thorn; &thorn;re at a strok.|&thorn;at is to seie. his owene soule.  his wilful heerar&meper; &amp; him &thorn;at &thorn;ei|falsli sclaundren &Verbar;</P>
<P>Of &thorn;e &thorn;ridde it is writen.  Ge. iiii<SUP>o</SUP>.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Gen. iv. 8-12.</NOTE> Hou &thorn;at cursid Caym.|slou&yogh; his innocent bro&thorn;ir Abel&meper; &amp; hou his blood cried to God|from &thorn;e er&thorn;e/ for seint Ion sei&thorn;. Apoc. vi<SUP>o</SUP>. 'Vidi subtus altare<MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="92b">| animas interfectorum | propter verbum dei &amp; propter testimonium|quod habebant.  Et clamabant voce magna dicentes/ vsquequo|domine sanctus &amp; verus non iudicas &amp; vindicas sanguinem nostrum|de hijs qui habitant in terra'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Apoc. vi. 9.</NOTE>/  Seynt Ion sei&thorn;. I saw&yogh; vndir &thorn;e|auter &thorn;e soules of hem &thorn;at weren slayn for &thorn;e word of God&meper; &|witnesse &thorn;at &thorn;ei hadden/ &amp; &thorn;ei crieden wi&thorn; a greet vois seiyng/|holi Lord &amp; trewe&meper; til whanne schalt &thorn;ou abide/ or &thorn;ou wilt|iugge and venge oure blod on hem &thorn;at dwellen in er&thorn;e/ And|it is seide vnto hem&meper; &thorn;at &thorn;ei schulden be stille/ &yogh;it a litil while&meper;|til her felowis be comen/ &amp; her bri&thorn;eren &thorn;at ben to be slayn&meper; as|&thorn;ei ben hem silf<NOTE PLACE="foot">W. V. 'I si&yogh;e undir an auter the soules of men sleyn for the word of God,|and for witnessing that thei hadden.  And thei crieden with greet voys,|seiynge, Hou longe, Lord, holy and trewe, demyst thou not, and vengist our|blood of thes that dwellen in erthe? and it is seid to hem, that thei shulden|reste &yogh;it a litil tyme, til the euen seruauntes of hem be fulfilled, and the|britheren of hem, that ben to be slayn, as and thei.'  1388, 'Y say undur the|auter the soulis of men slayn for the word of God, and for the witnessing that|thei hadden.  And thei crieden with a greet vois, and seiden, How long thou,|Lord, that art hooli and trewe, demest not, and vengest not oure blood of these|that dwellen in the erthe? and it was seide to hem, that thei schulden reste|&yogh;it a litil tyme, til the noumbre of her felowis and of her britheren ben fulfillid,|that ben to be slayn as also thei.'</NOTE> &Verbar; vndirstonde &thorn;at God forfendi&thorn;&meper; al vnlawful
<PB N="99">|sleeyng/ as Crisostom declari&thorn;. om. LI/  'Percutere est iniuste|percutere/ qui autem propter iustitie causam percutit&meper; percutere|non videtur. percutit enim non vt suum dolorem vindicet&meper; sed vt|illius animam saluet. sicut vero iusta ira non est ira sed diligencia&meper;|sic iusta percussio non est percussio&meper; sed correpcio'<NOTE PLACE="foot">S. Ioan. Chrysostomus, <I>Homilia LI (Opera</I>, ed. 1547, tom. ii, col. 1112).</NOTE>/  To smyt|taken bi it silf&meper; is vniustli to smyt/ forso&thorn;e he &thorn;at smyti&thorn;&meper; for|&thorn;e cause of ri&yogh;t-|wisenes/ he is not sen for to smyt&meper; bi title of <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="93a">|Goddis lawe/ forso&thorn;e he smyti&thorn; not to venge&meper; his owene wreechful|herte/ but to do &thorn;e wille of God&meper; &amp; saue his neibours soule/ as|iust wra&thorn;&thorn;e is no wra&thorn;&thorn;e&meper; but a feruent diligence/ so ri&yogh;twise|smyting is no smyting&meper; but a iust amending/ for bi suche a|feruent loue&meper; Phines slow&yogh; to lecchours/ &amp; turned &thorn;e wra&thorn;&thorn;e of|God&meper; from &thorn;e children of Isrel/ as it is writen. Numeri. xxv<SUP>o</SUP>.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Num. xxv. 6-8.</NOTE>/|Also God sent his oostis&meper;  Titus and Vaspasian/ two &amp; fourty|wyntir&meper; aftir &thorn;at Crist was slayn/ for to venge Cristis dee&thorn;&meper;|vpon &thorn;e cursid Iewis/ as it is writen. Mat. xxii<SUP>o</SUP>. 'Missis exercitibus|suis perdidit homisidas illos &amp; ciuitatem eorum succendit'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulg. Matt. xxii. 7.</NOTE> &Verbar;</P>
<P>Fyue &thorn;ingis men must avoide&meper; whanne &thorn;ei schullen go to|bataile/ for &thorn;ei ben a&yogh;enst &thorn;is heest. &amp; &thorn;us sei&thorn; seint Austin/|'Nocendi cupiditas vlcisendi crudelitas implacabilis animus. feritas|rebellandi libido dominandi. &amp; sique sunt talia. hec sunt que in|bello iure culpantur'/  Hec Augustinus | contra Faustum<NOTE PLACE="foot">S. Augustinus, <I>On the Manichaean Heresy</I> (reply to Faustus), xxii. 7|(Migne, tom. 42, col. 447).</NOTE> &Verbar; &THORN;at <MILESTONE UNIT="folio" N="93b">|is to seie.  Coueitise of noiyng. cruelte of vengeyng. an vnpesible|mynde. feersenes of fi&yogh;tyng. lust of lordschiping. and what &thorn;at|ben lijke to &thorn;ise/ for &thorn;ise ben &thorn;o &thorn;ingis&meper; &thorn;at of ri&yogh;t ben blamed|in bataile/</P>
